00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:13.920
[Amit Varma]: slash IVM. Pooja, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Hi, thank you. Thanks for having

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:18.960
[Amit Varma]: me over. Pooja, before we start talking about your book, The Lost Decade, tell me something

00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:24.080
[Amit Varma]: about your journey so far. How did you get interested in economics? And how did you become

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:30.840
[Guest]: an economic journalist? Okay, so it's by accident, I did not make a conscious decision to either

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:36.840
[Guest]: study economics or join journalism. When I was in school, I actually first I wanted to

00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:40.840
[Guest]: be a lawyer. And then I wanted to join the civil services. And those were the two options

00:04:40.840 --> 00:04:48.080
[Guest]: I was very keen on. But my family dissuaded me from both and not a very, I mean, you know,

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:51.880
[Guest]: very light conversations, no serious discussions, but mostly they would be like, No, you may

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:57.720
[Guest]: not like that, you know, those are tough jobs and all that. And so I hadn't really given

00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:03.360
[Guest]: much thought to what I wanted to do. And my cousin, who's a big influence on me, took

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:08.080
[Guest]: up economics. And he's one year ahead of me. And he took up economics. And just because

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:13.160
[Guest]: he had taken up economics, I also applied for economics, although I was a science student.

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:18.400
[Guest]: And I got through in Kamla Nehru College, which tends to have a high cutoffs and is

00:05:18.400 --> 00:05:23.640
[Guest]: considered a good college in Delhi University for economics after Stephens, LSR and SRCC

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:28.280
[Guest]: it's considered quite good. And I didn't want to let go of that seat. So, you know, so sort

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:33.920
[Guest]: of following in the footsteps of my cousin, I took up economics. And I found that a year

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:38.720
[Guest]: after he finished his first year of economics, and by the time I had already joined, he decided

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:43.640
[Guest]: he didn't like economics, and he switched over to physics. He restarted his graduation

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:49.400
[Guest]: doing physics, but I carried on with economics, I was beginning to enjoy the subject, I had

00:05:49.400 --> 00:05:55.360
[Guest]: a good set of friends in college and all that. And I finished graduation and there was a

00:05:55.360 --> 00:06:00.800
[Guest]: lot of sort of peer pressure, everybody was sitting for their CAT exam, and people were

00:06:00.800 --> 00:06:05.520
[Guest]: considering where to do their MBA and all that. And there's this one friend of mine

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:09.480
[Guest]: in college who, you know, one day told me that a couple of days later, she was planning

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:15.360
[Guest]: to go to the North Campus where she wanted to apply for the entrance exam for Delhi School

00:06:15.360 --> 00:06:20.080
[Guest]: of Economics for a master's in economics. And she was looking, you know, for basically

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:24.680
[Guest]: somebody to go along with her and if I was interested. And I said that, you know, if

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:30.480
[Guest]: you're applying for a master's, I will also. And we both went and applied, we sat for the

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:36.520
[Guest]: entrance exam, and she never made it and I did. And so I joined Delhi School of Economics

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:43.560
[Guest]: and I found it really, really difficult. They really expect you to work very hard. And most

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:49.640
[Guest]: of my batchmates started preparing for their, you know, they wanted to do their PhDs overseas

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:55.160
[Guest]: and I could tell that I would not be able to work that hard. And therefore, I put in

00:06:55.160 --> 00:07:02.320
[Guest]: my request in the placement cell for placements. Now, this is the year 2000, where the economy

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:08.440
[Guest]: was not doing very well. And there were very few job offers and therefore, relative to

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:12.360
[Guest]: the number of students and therefore, they had a rule. And the rule was that, you know,

00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:16.840
[Guest]: if you get a job offer after sitting for an interview, and you don't accept it, then you

00:07:16.840 --> 00:07:23.960
[Guest]: have to wait for everybody else to get placed and only then you can apply for another interview.

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:28.500
[Guest]: And my first job offer came from a newspaper, Business Standard. And therefore, the choice

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:33.000
[Guest]: for me was whether to accept that or to not accept that and risk not getting any other

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:37.760
[Guest]: job at all, because I have to wait for everybody else to get placed. And that's how I joined

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:43.640
[Guest]: Business Standard financial paper. And that's how I sort of came to business journalism.

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:47.680
[Guest]: Because nobody in my family is a journalist, and I'd never thought of journalism as a career

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:53.240
[Guest]: option. And I landed in business journalism. And I quite liked it. I had good colleagues

00:07:53.240 --> 00:08:00.080
[Guest]: and very good bosses and editors, and I've just stayed on. So that's how I came to economic

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:01.080
[Amit Varma]: journalism.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:04.080
[Amit Varma]: Well, thank God for us, you stayed on. And it's interesting how you know, when you describe

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:08.600
[Amit Varma]: the role of happenstance in your life, and reading your book, it struck me, as we'll

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:13.320
[Amit Varma]: discuss later how happenstance and events that seem unconnected with economics actually

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:18.600
[Amit Varma]: played such a big role in what subsequently happened. So tell me, you know, when you were

00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:25.080
[Amit Varma]: starting, yeah, so tell me when you were sort of starting off, getting into economics, doing

00:08:25.080 --> 00:08:29.800
[Amit Varma]: journalism and all of that, who were the thinkers who influenced you? Like, what were the kind

00:08:29.800 --> 00:08:34.240
[Amit Varma]: of books that had an influence on you? And importantly, over the period of time, from

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:39.120
[Amit Varma]: the time you studied economics in college to let's say today, how have your thoughts

00:08:39.120 --> 00:08:41.200
[Amit Varma]: on economics per se evolved?

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:46.440
[Guest]: Right. So, you know, unlike how it is in JNU, in Delhi School of Economics, the way they

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:52.200
[Guest]: teach you economics is very different. There's an influence of market economics led thinking.

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:57.760
[Guest]: And consciously or unconsciously, there are these giants, you know, there, and especially

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:03.400
[Guest]: because I was in college, you know, before 2000. So the big influences at that point

00:09:03.400 --> 00:09:09.320
[Guest]: in time on campus in the school and therefore on me, were people like Dr. Manmohan Singh,

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:13.800
[Guest]: you know, Montek Singh Ahluwalia. So their reputation at that point was a little different

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:20.880
[Guest]: than what it is now. And there was a scholarship in college named after Dr. Manmohan Singh,

00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:26.840
[Guest]: and Professor Kaushik Basu, and people like that, you know, and our teachers were very

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:32.200
[Guest]: clear that, you know, the market economy is the way to go forward. And we didn't have

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:38.560
[Guest]: textbooks for every topic, we had a series of readings. So, you know, few paras from

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:44.880
[Guest]: various writers, most of them international economists, very few Indian writers we had,

00:09:44.880 --> 00:09:50.840
[Guest]: you know, in our course curriculum material. So, at that point in time in college, most

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:56.600
[Guest]: of my reading on economics was limited to what was prescribed in course. Thereafter,

00:09:56.600 --> 00:10:04.560
[Guest]: after I joined, you know, Business Standard, I found that a lot of what was taught in class,

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:08.880
[Guest]: I was, especially because I had macroeconomics and public finance as my optional papers,

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:14.600
[Guest]: a lot of that I was beginning to see how it plays out, you know, in the real economy,

00:10:14.600 --> 00:10:21.720
[Guest]: and all the various manifestations of it. And honestly, I did not read much of anything

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:27.520
[Guest]: in the first few years of my career related to economics. So I didn't, at that point read,

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:33.800
[Guest]: you know, Amartya Sen or Raghuram Rajan when his book came out later. I read all of that

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:39.480
[Guest]: quite late. And I don't think, you know, other than what I had learned in class, I don't

00:10:39.480 --> 00:10:44.880
[Guest]: think I had too many influences in terms of what I had read. By the time I started reading

00:10:44.880 --> 00:10:51.520
[Guest]: all these big names, I myself had well formed ideas about what goes on in the economy, based

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:56.480
[Guest]: on what I was taught in class and how I'd seen it play out, you know, in the real economy

00:10:56.480 --> 00:10:57.480
[Guest]: in India.

00:10:57.480 --> 00:11:01.720
[Amit Varma]: Right. So, you know, before we start talking about the last decade, which is really about

00:11:01.720 --> 00:11:06.760
[Amit Varma]: the last 10 years, and how we sort of lost the way, you know, turned it back a little

00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:12.400
[Amit Varma]: bit and then lost away again, I'd like you to set a little bit of context in terms of,

00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:17.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, I often as someone who grew up in the 80s and the 90s, I often take it for granted

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:23.240
[Amit Varma]: that my shared experiences are shared by everyone. But I often forget that 60% of India today

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:29.160
[Amit Varma]: was born after the liberalisation of 91. And that's such an important turning point in

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:35.280
[Amit Varma]: our economy. So can you sort of give me a sense of what our economy was like, say from

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:39.840
[Amit Varma]: independence to 91? What were the sort of guiding philosophies? And how that changed

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:40.840
[Amit Varma]: in 91?

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:46.360
[Guest]: Yes, in fact, Amit, I myself, I feel, you know, when I speak to youngsters, I feel exactly

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:52.480
[Guest]: the same, but they have no idea how life was, you know, before 1991, or for those of us,

00:11:52.480 --> 00:12:00.160
[Guest]: you know, who are older, who are like past 35. And so to speak of it in terms of everyday

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:06.040
[Guest]: life, you'd recall that an example that is often given is, you know, you wanted to buy

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:11.480
[Guest]: a car, you could afford to buy a car, and your choices were limited to one or two brands,

00:12:11.480 --> 00:12:15.280
[Guest]: you may like them, you may not like them, quality did not matter, because the quantity

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:20.680
[Guest]: was so less. And even for those few cars that were manufactured every year, there was a

00:12:20.680 --> 00:12:26.880
[Guest]: long list of people waiting to buy them. And therefore, anything, you know, would go. Now,

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:34.560
[Guest]: in 1947, the two phases before 1991, and after 1991, I think the average person in India

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:41.920
[Guest]: seems to be the forgotten or doesn't realize at all, that until 1947, Indian economy had

00:12:41.920 --> 00:12:49.400
[Guest]: been, you know, under colonial sort of control. And most of the economic policy was driven

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:55.280
[Guest]: by the Second World War's requirements, the Indian economy had been geared, you know,

00:12:55.280 --> 00:13:02.880
[Guest]: the resources were being taken away, to provide for the Second World War. And, you know, be

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:09.560
[Guest]: it in terms of foreign exchange, be it in terms of exports, you could not import things,

00:13:09.560 --> 00:13:14.600
[Guest]: even if you could afford them, there were regulations, they were import controls. And

00:13:14.600 --> 00:13:20.720
[Guest]: all of these rules and regulations were written into Indian law, economic policy, which a

00:13:20.720 --> 00:13:25.280
[Guest]: lot of it has not been shared even today, you know, those were the sort of the founding

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:32.120
[Guest]: principles of a lot of economic policy, and much of it was shared in 1991. But a lot of

00:13:32.120 --> 00:13:38.280
[Guest]: it survives, we still need to, you know, get rid of those, that control mentality. And

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:43.160
[Guest]: what that control mentality is that before 1947, which carried on for some time after

00:13:43.160 --> 00:13:48.840
[Guest]: that, that everything would be determined by the needs of the war. So you have to, you

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:53.600
[Guest]: cannot import, you know, things like steel, or if you're producing things like steel,

00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:58.320
[Guest]: it has to be used for a certain purpose, which is determined by not what is good for the

00:13:58.320 --> 00:14:02.920
[Guest]: rest of the economy or people like you and me, but you know, what is good for the Second

00:14:02.920 --> 00:14:09.520
[Guest]: World War, Great Britain. Now, once that was done, when we got freedom, I think the immediate

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:15.080
[Guest]: response of the government at that point, with the heavy influence of Pandit Nehru was

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:20.280
[Guest]: that we need to reconstruct the economy, which had been under colonial rule, and which had

00:14:20.280 --> 00:14:25.920
[Guest]: taken this huge hit because of the Second World War. And how do we do it? From what

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:33.560
[Guest]: we understand, the private sector was small, and not in a shape to take up the huge challenge.

00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:38.440
[Guest]: And therefore, the public sector had to be relied on and it had to be strengthened. Now,

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:44.040
[Guest]: we all know how that philosophy, and of course, there was also the fear of economic imperialism,

00:14:44.040 --> 00:14:48.480
[Guest]: we had just gained political freedom. And I think the country at that point in time

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:52.240
[Guest]: did not want to surrender economic freedom, and therefore the fear of foreign capital

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:57.640
[Guest]: and foreign investments. And I think those are the two sort of guiding principles at

00:14:57.640 --> 00:15:04.000
[Guest]: that point in time, which led to what is called Nehruvian socialism. When we criticize Nehruvian

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:09.080
[Guest]: socialism, and I definitely am not a fan of it. But when we criticize it, we must remember

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:15.760
[Guest]: the context in which that came as a policy response. Very soon, the limitations of that

00:15:15.760 --> 00:15:23.320
[Guest]: kind of thinking became apparent. But it was a little too late to do anything about it.

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:30.240
[Guest]: I think the government's attention was drawn to other things, political things, etc. And

00:15:30.240 --> 00:15:37.640
[Guest]: this sort of carried on. And I think as Sunil Kilnani talks about in his book, Idea of India,

00:15:37.640 --> 00:15:42.920
[Guest]: what this did deliver was that the economy was stable, it did not grow very fast, but

00:15:42.920 --> 00:15:50.120
[Guest]: it was quite stable. Then came the Indira Gandhi variety of socialism, which had a lot

00:15:50.120 --> 00:15:58.960
[Guest]: to do with government spending led economic policies. And also later on, nationalization

00:15:58.960 --> 00:16:05.560
[Guest]: and those, you know, the charter, that was, I think the seven points, I think that were

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:11.360
[Guest]: announced. That was quite damaging. That was very, very damaging for the economy. And of

00:16:11.360 --> 00:16:18.000
[Guest]: course, there was not much growth. But there was also a worsening of the fiscal parameters

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:26.440
[Guest]: and macroeconomic stability. And because these parameters were weakening, by the 80s, there

00:16:26.440 --> 00:16:33.680
[Guest]: was a realization amongst Indian experts. And Mrs. Gandhi here and there does show some

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:38.960
[Guest]: openness to listening to these things, including a couple of times when Dr. Manmohan Singh

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:46.280
[Guest]: sort of, in various capacities, tried to explain how Indian economic policy was completely

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:53.420
[Guest]: off course. And some little bit corrections do begin to take place in the 80s. Bank nationalization

00:16:53.420 --> 00:17:01.280
[Guest]: has sort of indirect good influence on India's saving rate, and therefore investment rate.

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:07.160
[Guest]: And those little sort of low hanging reforms that were undertaken, that were taken up in

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:13.520
[Guest]: the 80s, begin to show a little few results, which carries on when Rajiv Gandhi becomes

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:21.400
[Guest]: the Prime Minister. But after that political instability and, you know, incompleteness

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:27.160
[Guest]: of the reforms, inability to think through a lot of things meant that the economy was

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:36.680
[Guest]: not doing well. And the fiscal parameters started weakening, you know, more and more.

00:17:36.680 --> 00:17:42.800
[Guest]: And after that, so there was this one external shock of the Gulf War, which really weakened

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:48.080
[Guest]: India's external position a lot, because we had been borrowing so much. And you know,

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:53.840
[Guest]: those were the days when the government could just print more money and pay for anything

00:17:53.840 --> 00:17:58.400
[Guest]: that was not covered by its own revenue. So the difference between its expenditure and

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:04.560
[Guest]: its revenue was simply covered by printing more money. And that meant a lot of short

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:10.880
[Guest]: term borrowings that they kept rolling over. And therefore, you know, this like the shock

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:16.800
[Guest]: of the Gulf War sort of tipped the balance of payments into a dangerous zone and the

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:24.440
[Guest]: famous 1991 crisis happened. So that's what was the story before 1991, that a lot of bad

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:30.520
[Guest]: decisions, some of them under the influence of the context of those, you know, that era,

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:35.480
[Guest]: but some of them because of complete disregard for what is good for the economy.

00:18:35.480 --> 00:18:41.880
[Amit Varma]: I think it's also kind of pertinent to point out that more than as much as policies that

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:46.360
[Amit Varma]: sort of were in place is also pertinent to point out the mindset behind them. Now, Nehru,

00:18:46.360 --> 00:18:49.800
[Amit Varma]: who is again, a great statesman, I admire him, you know, I think India was lucky to

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:53.520
[Amit Varma]: have him as its first Prime Minister, but and in terms of economic policies, like you

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:59.360
[Amit Varma]: rightly said, I mean, the sort of soft socialism he followed was the flavor of the times and

00:18:59.360 --> 00:19:03.720
[Amit Varma]: he wouldn't have known better at the time and he died before he could correct if he

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:07.800
[Amit Varma]: would have been open to it. But essentially, the two of the fundamental problems was one

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:12.920
[Amit Varma]: was a distrust of private enterprise and a distrust indeed of the profit motive. Like

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:18.480
[Amit Varma]: Nehru once famously said to JRD Tata, do not talk to me of profit, it is a dirty word.

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:23.480
[Amit Varma]: And that distrust meant that he looked at private enterprise as necessarily something

00:19:23.480 --> 00:19:28.520
[Amit Varma]: that is exploitative of the people, which also, you know, brought back those memories

00:19:28.520 --> 00:19:33.720
[Amit Varma]: of colonialism and so on. He didn't see it as a positive gig, some game it is by which

00:19:33.720 --> 00:19:38.240
[Amit Varma]: everyone benefits and economies grow. And therefore, the second part of his mindset,

00:19:38.240 --> 00:19:43.480
[Amit Varma]: which was so fatally flawed, as it were, was the whole command and control mindset that

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:47.640
[Amit Varma]: the government will do everything it will plan every aspect of the economy. And I think

00:19:47.640 --> 00:19:53.280
[Amit Varma]: by the time we sort of knew it wasn't working and Indira came to power, Indira moved leftward

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:59.560
[Amit Varma]: for political compulsions as much as you know, any conviction in her economic policies, because

00:19:59.560 --> 00:20:03.880
[Amit Varma]: she had to distinguish herself from the syndicate in the Congress, which she was fighting against

00:20:03.880 --> 00:20:09.680
[Amit Varma]: and the leftward tilt was a sort of a rebranding. And then she went into populism of Gareebi

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:14.760
[Amit Varma]: Hatao and following these, you know, so called pro poor policies, or they actually hurt the

00:20:14.760 --> 00:20:18.280
[Amit Varma]: poor more than they help them. And and this is a theme again, that you touch on in your

00:20:18.280 --> 00:20:21.560
[Amit Varma]: book a lot. And I'm going to come back to you later and ask about that later in this

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:26.960
[Amit Varma]: episode about the interplay between politics and economics. And and basically, as you've

00:20:26.960 --> 00:20:31.800
[Amit Varma]: summed up, we were sort of limping our way through making small corrections here and

00:20:31.800 --> 00:20:36.800
[Amit Varma]: there, but the fundamental mindsets weren't changed. And would you say that the changes

00:20:36.800 --> 00:20:43.400
[Amit Varma]: that happened in 1991, came not so much from conviction as circumstances, because we had

00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:48.880
[Amit Varma]: that balance of payments crisis, we were in a fix, we have we had no option but to RCIMF

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:51.760
[Amit Varma]: for help. And these were sort of their conditionalities.

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:57.560
[Guest]: So, Amit, I agree with what you say on both Mrs. Gandhi and Pandit Nehru, except that

00:20:57.560 --> 00:21:03.200
[Guest]: my small point here would be that I'm not so sure the Indian private sector, barring

00:21:03.200 --> 00:21:06.720
[Guest]: one or two examples, such as JRD Tata, and it is absolutely wrong to I think, nationalize

00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:13.600
[Guest]: Air India. But barring those two examples, was really our private sector willing to,

00:21:13.600 --> 00:21:20.240
[Guest]: you know, enter into these highly competitive and long gestation high risk areas, you know,

00:21:20.240 --> 00:21:25.960
[Guest]: where the public sector was pushed into by Pandit Nehru? I don't think so. I don't think

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:29.680
[Guest]: that you know, the Indian private sector was roaring to go into these areas, and they were

00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:33.480
[Guest]: denied a chance. Private sector was not banned. Let's not forget that.

00:21:33.480 --> 00:21:38.640
[Amit Varma]: No, I'd argue that they weren't given the opportunity in the first place. Like the example

00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:43.240
[Amit Varma]: that I often like to give, you know, to contrast the late 80s, and just maybe seven or eight

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:49.040
[Amit Varma]: years later, is that is you look at something like say, telephones and airlines, you just,

00:21:49.040 --> 00:21:53.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, in 87, 88, or so on, you had five year waiting list, 10 year waiting list for

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:58.520
[Amit Varma]: telephones. Yes. Airlines were outside the bounds of most Indians. And the moment those

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:03.080
[Amit Varma]: sectors got opened up in the private sector actually got the opportunity. You were flooded

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:07.720
[Amit Varma]: with both variety and value when you saw the result of competition. So today, it's hard

00:22:07.720 --> 00:22:12.280
[Amit Varma]: to imagine that you had to wait five years to get a telephone and that to only the extremely

00:22:12.280 --> 00:22:17.720
[Amit Varma]: privileged could afford it. So you know, in that sense, and you know, I wish things like

00:22:17.720 --> 00:22:21.320
[Amit Varma]: agriculture and education had also been opened up in the same way.

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:26.880
[Guest]: Yes, but I just, you know, nuance that a little bit by saying that, you know, if you were

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:30.480
[Guest]: giving these permits, you know, for a limited production, you can produce this, but you

00:22:30.480 --> 00:22:36.520
[Guest]: can only produce this much, you can't sort of that was the control, right? Now, what

00:22:36.520 --> 00:22:42.440
[Guest]: that did was, that was not so much anti private sector, it was pro business, if you wanted

00:22:42.440 --> 00:22:47.400
[Guest]: only a few companies to be in that sector and do well, or I mean, I'm not saying you

00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:53.080
[Guest]: wanted to, but that's what it ended up doing, you know, that that only two car manufacturers

00:22:53.080 --> 00:22:58.360
[Guest]: can make cars, and therefore, they do well, but, you know, but the rest who are willing

00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:03.880
[Guest]: to make cars, there's an entry barrier, you know, what I mean? So it's not exactly anti

00:23:03.880 --> 00:23:09.040
[Guest]: private sector. But the problem is that, you know, you're selecting one, so it's not socialism,

00:23:09.040 --> 00:23:14.120
[Guest]: you know, it's not capitalism, you're choosing a few capitalists, who can, you know, make

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:19.080
[Guest]: super normal profits, but by preventing the rest of the private sector to enter that area.

00:23:19.080 --> 00:23:21.000
[Guest]: So that is the model they've operated.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.440
[Amit Varma]: Right. So in fact, I'll ask you a question here, which I was actually saving for later.

00:23:24.440 --> 00:23:28.320
[Amit Varma]: But it makes sense. Now, like, you know, even in your book, you've used the two phrases

00:23:28.320 --> 00:23:32.520
[Amit Varma]: pro business versus pro markets. And this is something I think a lot of people don't

00:23:32.520 --> 00:23:38.340
[Amit Varma]: get that, you know, and a lot of market supporters, often, you know, they have the crony capitalism

00:23:38.340 --> 00:23:42.160
[Amit Varma]: thrown in their faces. And, you know, what about this? And actually, what is good for

00:23:42.160 --> 00:23:47.640
[Amit Varma]: markets and what is good for a few select businesses are very, very different things.

00:23:47.640 --> 00:23:51.440
[Amit Varma]: Can you elaborate on the distinction between, you know, being pro business and being pro

00:23:51.440 --> 00:23:52.440
[Amit Varma]: markets?

00:23:52.440 --> 00:23:58.520
[Guest]: Yes, absolutely. So, you know, you're pro business, when you create a policy for a sector

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:05.360
[Guest]: specifying norms, where only few people can enter and qualify, and you leave out the rest,

00:24:05.360 --> 00:24:10.720
[Guest]: then you're not pro markets, you're pro business, you're supposedly, you know, you're not saying,

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:19.160
[Guest]: so let's take the example of education today. You're not saying that education, only ABC

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:22.960
[Guest]: business houses can enter education. That's not what your policy says. But your policy

00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:28.320
[Guest]: says that if you want to set up an engineering college, you must be able to put so much money

00:24:28.320 --> 00:24:32.400
[Guest]: into the laboratory, you must be able to put so much money into the you know, initial permit

00:24:32.400 --> 00:24:36.240
[Guest]: that we give you, you must be able to put everything is defined in terms of you must

00:24:36.240 --> 00:24:41.120
[Guest]: be able to do this much, this much, this much. And when you look at that criteria, that becomes

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:47.560
[Guest]: exclusionary. I may not, I may be running, you know, let's not say higher education institutes,

00:24:47.560 --> 00:24:51.240
[Guest]: but let's talk about, for instance, you know, schools, I may be running something under

00:24:51.240 --> 00:24:55.980
[Guest]: a flyover, and I'm really good, every student I'm teaching is coming out with flying colors

00:24:55.980 --> 00:25:02.120
[Guest]: and passing examinations, but I can't qualify to get that licensed campus, because your

00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:07.680
[Guest]: rules are excluding me. So in this case, you're not pro markets, you're pro business, even

00:25:07.680 --> 00:25:11.440
[Guest]: though you're not saying, you know, private sector is not allowed, you know, so this is

00:25:11.440 --> 00:25:17.720
[Guest]: a very crude example I've given, but we see a lot of this, even today in many sectors,

00:25:17.720 --> 00:25:24.280
[Guest]: where do you think you and I can just decide to go and set up, you know, a cell phone company,

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:31.680
[Guest]: or an airline, you know, we can't, we can't even if we had all that money, all that expertise

00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:37.920
[Guest]: that those who are in that sector today have, the entry barriers into that sector are high.

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:43.520
[Guest]: And therefore, there is no competition. And therefore, it is not pro markets policy, it

00:25:43.520 --> 00:25:45.560
[Amit Varma]: is still in many ways pro business policy.

00:25:45.560 --> 00:25:51.120
[Amit Varma]: Exactly. And a lot of people don't get the distinction of what is, you know, good for

00:25:51.120 --> 00:25:56.800
[Amit Varma]: markets and capitalism may not be what capitalists actually want. So, you know, this distinction

00:25:56.800 --> 00:26:03.280
[Amit Varma]: is sort of important to make. Going back quickly to 91 sort of, one, were the reforms driven

00:26:03.280 --> 00:26:09.880
[Amit Varma]: by conviction? Or were they forced by circumstance or a combination of the two? And two, how far

00:26:09.880 --> 00:26:14.360
[Amit Varma]: do you think, you know, what difference did the reforms make? And do you think they went

00:26:14.360 --> 00:26:16.920
[Amit Varma]: far enough? Like, where did we fall short?

00:26:16.920 --> 00:26:22.840
[Guest]: Yeah, so it depends on whose conviction you're talking about, you know, the economists and

00:26:22.840 --> 00:26:27.640
[Guest]: select bureaucrats, they were convinced about what had to be done, they knew exactly what

00:26:27.640 --> 00:26:32.360
[Guest]: had to be done, even back in the 1970s. You know, there is a paper that Dr. Manmohan Singh,

00:26:32.360 --> 00:26:38.240
[Guest]: for instance, had written, and I think if I'm not wrong, 1971, where he had said that,

00:26:38.240 --> 00:26:43.480
[Guest]: you know, how, in fact, even his PhD thesis, he has written about how Indian policies are

00:26:43.480 --> 00:26:49.440
[Guest]: all wrong, and you know, they will land us into trouble. So, Indian economists and Indian,

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:52.880
[Guest]: many of the technocrats were fully aware of what was going wrong and what needed to be

00:26:52.880 --> 00:26:59.600
[Guest]: done. But there was no buy-in from the politicians. And there was no political conviction. By

00:26:59.600 --> 00:27:07.240
[Guest]: 1991, I think politicians were left with no choice. And we see that the IMF lays down

00:27:07.240 --> 00:27:12.440
[Guest]: its conditions. And Mr. Yashwant Sinha, I think was the finance minister, and he's sort

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:17.560
[Guest]: of not able to go through with that. The government changes, P. V. Narasimha Rao comes and he

00:27:17.560 --> 00:27:23.520
[Guest]: begins to look for a finance minister. And he's forced to look for finance ministers

00:27:23.520 --> 00:27:28.480
[Guest]: that the IMF will trust. His first choice is I. G. Patel. I. G. Patel declines. And

00:27:28.480 --> 00:27:32.880
[Guest]: therefore, I think I. G. Patel suggests that, you know, Manmohan Singh would be a good option.

00:27:32.880 --> 00:27:38.680
[Guest]: And therefore, he goes to Manmohan Singh. And Manmohan Singh comes up, I mean, he comes

00:27:38.680 --> 00:27:42.680
[Guest]: up with his list, but already when he comes into office, on his table, there is a list

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:47.000
[Guest]: of things that have to be done, which have come from the IMF. But that doesn't mean that

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:51.920
[Guest]: if Manmohan Singh and his team of, you know, I call them the rescuers, you know, if they

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:56.220
[Guest]: had no list arriving from the IMF on what all needs to be done for that bailout package

00:27:56.220 --> 00:28:00.280
[Guest]: to be approved, he had not done the same thing. I think he would have also probably come up

00:28:00.280 --> 00:28:06.160
[Guest]: with a pretty similar list and done the same thing. And so definitely what was done was

00:28:06.160 --> 00:28:12.600
[Guest]: because the politician could no longer postpone these decisions and could no longer tell the

00:28:12.600 --> 00:28:17.640
[Guest]: economists and the technocrats that I'm not going to do this. And in that sense, it was

00:28:17.640 --> 00:28:24.840
[Guest]: driven by the crisis. But I don't give much credit to the IMF for the way the reforms

00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:29.080
[Guest]: were designed, because there's enough evidence, you know, that these things were being talked

00:28:29.080 --> 00:28:34.840
[Guest]: up about in the Indian policy circles much before that, including in the official papers.

00:28:34.840 --> 00:28:39.520
[Guest]: I think Rakesh Mohan has sort of documented a lot of this, especially about the industrial

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:45.120
[Guest]: policy and the de-licensing, etc. Yeah, so that's to talk about the conviction. What

00:28:45.120 --> 00:28:52.200
[Guest]: the reforms did was that wherever the economy was sort of, like we discussed, putting these

00:28:52.200 --> 00:29:00.680
[Guest]: conditions and restrictions and asking for, I mean, wherever it was operating under license,

00:29:00.680 --> 00:29:05.520
[Guest]: those things were removed. Foreign capital was less restrictive. I mean, they had to

00:29:05.520 --> 00:29:12.120
[Guest]: open up to foreign capital. Many areas that had been reserved exclusively for public sector

00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:17.880
[Guest]: had to be opened. Trade barriers had to be reduced. And I think later on, I don't know

00:29:17.880 --> 00:29:22.440
[Guest]: if this was prescribed by the IMF or not. I need to study that. But later on, I think

00:29:22.440 --> 00:29:26.920
[Guest]: one of the biggest reforms that does not get talked about in layman's circles is, you know,

00:29:26.920 --> 00:29:32.120
[Guest]: the understanding between the Reserve Bank of India, the governor at that point was C.

00:29:32.120 --> 00:29:37.440
[Guest]: Rangarajan and finance ministry headed by Manmohan Singh that, you know, printing of

00:29:37.440 --> 00:29:44.200
[Guest]: money to provide for the fiscal deficit, that will just not go on. That was a very big reform.

00:29:44.200 --> 00:29:48.560
[Guest]: I forgot to mention that the rupee was at that point in time not floating like it is

00:29:48.560 --> 00:29:56.080
[Guest]: now. It was a controlled, it was a fixed currency. And because of which, you know, it is an artificially

00:29:56.080 --> 00:30:03.960
[Guest]: strong currency. So there were two rounds of devaluation, because of which the, so what

00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:09.320
[Guest]: happens when your currency is artificially, you know, kept at a level. In the international

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:15.280
[Guest]: world, it costs X to buy something, for instance, petrol, you know, the price of petrol is X,

00:30:15.280 --> 00:30:20.600
[Guest]: but your currency is artificially up there. So your economy is not responding appropriately

00:30:20.600 --> 00:30:25.640
[Guest]: to the price movement internationally of a product because your currency is fixed. So

00:30:25.640 --> 00:30:32.560
[Guest]: your demand internally was not adjusting properly. And by those two rounds of devaluation, that

00:30:32.560 --> 00:30:37.120
[Guest]: was gradually corrected. And eventually, of course, you know, the rupee became floating.

00:30:37.120 --> 00:30:43.640
[Guest]: So those were the kind of, you know, corrections in policy that took place. Now, those were

00:30:43.640 --> 00:30:50.280
[Guest]: all good and needed to be done. But that was the very basics. The really difficult thing

00:30:50.280 --> 00:30:58.280
[Guest]: to do was, you know, agriculture reforms, labor reforms, those have still not happened.

00:30:58.280 --> 00:31:03.880
[Guest]: And I don't see anybody even saying that those need to be done. That was my biggest worry

00:31:03.880 --> 00:31:11.600
[Guest]: that, you know, the political consensus, somehow, this thing doesn't even get mentioned. And

00:31:11.600 --> 00:31:16.280
[Guest]: in that sense, you know, reforms have not graduated to the second generation and third

00:31:16.280 --> 00:31:23.520
[Guest]: generation level. 25-26 years later, we still talk about change of FDI caps or liberalization

00:31:23.520 --> 00:31:28.680
[Guest]: of FDI caps as a reform. I don't think that should even be called a reform now. That should

00:31:28.680 --> 00:31:33.160
[Guest]: just be an everyday policy decision that somebody junior sitting in some ministry should be

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:39.200
[Guest]: able to just sign off. You know, so the word reforms itself has become so cheapened because

00:31:39.200 --> 00:31:43.120
[Guest]: the big reforms are not, you know, taking place.

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And would it be the case, I mean, the reforms momentum slowed in the mid 90s, and then seem

00:31:48.120 --> 00:31:52.680
[Amit Varma]: to almost disappear at some points. And part of the reason for that, if I may speculate,

00:31:52.680 --> 00:31:58.480
[Amit Varma]: is that, you know, the urgency of those reforms was no longer felt and the old political imperatives

00:31:58.480 --> 00:32:04.320
[Amit Varma]: came back in play. So even if for some of these period, you had, you know, people in

00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:09.720
[Amit Varma]: the finance ministry and the finance minister himself who were reform minded, it just became

00:32:09.720 --> 00:32:14.400
[Amit Varma]: much harder to push these reforms through. In some cases, the political impact would

00:32:14.400 --> 00:32:18.160
[Amit Varma]: be negative. And in some cases, the political impact would be so long term in the process

00:32:18.160 --> 00:32:21.640
[Amit Varma]: so arduous that it didn't make sense at all.

00:32:21.640 --> 00:32:27.360
[Guest]: So you're right that, you know, politicians first love is not reforms. So they have to

00:32:27.360 --> 00:32:32.800
[Guest]: be persuaded. Now, when you're making a case for reforms vis-a-vis other things they can

00:32:32.800 --> 00:32:39.800
[Guest]: do, you know, what they look at is that, I mean, you know, I think the experience of

00:32:39.800 --> 00:32:42.760
[Guest]: the Vajpayee government has sort of given a scare to our politicians, and they think

00:32:42.760 --> 00:32:50.200
[Guest]: that reforms don't get you reelected. And reforms sort of turn masses of voters against

00:32:50.200 --> 00:32:57.160
[Guest]: you. And to overcome that for a sitting government, I think to overcome that thought process,

00:32:57.160 --> 00:33:03.160
[Guest]: it becomes difficult. Also, because, you know, to understand what a reform is, what it will

00:33:03.160 --> 00:33:08.600
[Guest]: do, how it will play out in the economy is slightly difficult and wonkish. And often,

00:33:08.600 --> 00:33:15.160
[Guest]: it's not well understood. And I think the second thing that happens is that paradoxically,

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:22.240
[Guest]: you know, political parties want to make their opponents seem like they are not good at their

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:30.000
[Guest]: economic performance. And therefore, they oppose reforms, when they are in the opposition.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:34.280
[Guest]: So as it is to begin with, you know, for the sitting government, there is very little incentive

00:33:34.280 --> 00:33:38.480
[Guest]: and they, you know, the decision makers politically have to be really explained what needs to

00:33:38.480 --> 00:33:44.220
[Guest]: be done. And whatever little they might be willing to do, the opposition make is so noisy

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:49.280
[Guest]: and so obstructive, you know, that decisions become even more difficult to take. So for

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:55.280
[Guest]: example, let's take the example of GST. GST could have happened in the tenure of the UPA.

00:33:55.280 --> 00:34:02.400
[Guest]: It did not happen because the BJP ruled states did not support them. This is quite discussed

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:08.440
[Guest]: in the book at length in the second chapter. Or you take the example of, you know, land

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:14.520
[Guest]: reforms and labor reforms, which the Modi government attempted, but trade unions of

00:34:14.520 --> 00:34:20.960
[Guest]: their own, affiliated to their own political setup, opposed the labor reforms. And, you

00:34:20.960 --> 00:34:25.400
[Guest]: know, Mr. Modi met with them, but after he heard them out, he just vanishes from his

00:34:25.400 --> 00:34:33.720
[Guest]: agenda. And the Congress party's opposition to land reforms in parliament in 2015, again

00:34:33.720 --> 00:34:41.200
[Guest]: push land reforms off the agenda. So it is one that, you know, politicians when they

00:34:41.200 --> 00:34:48.240
[Guest]: are in office, economic reforms is not their agenda, is not high on their agenda. But whenever

00:34:48.240 --> 00:34:53.760
[Guest]: it comes up, you know, when, when the reformers in our government try to push it, there is

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:58.840
[Guest]: so much opposition from within the political parties and from the opposition that the reformers

00:34:58.840 --> 00:35:03.680
[Guest]: voices are getting drowned out. And we see this happening in governments ruled by all

00:35:03.680 --> 00:35:06.960
[Guest]: shapes of the political color. It's common.

00:35:06.960 --> 00:35:11.480
[Amit Varma]: Right. So, you know, let's kind of get to the book. Now, your book, of course, starts

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:17.800
[Amit Varma]: off in 2008. Get me up to speed with sort of where India is at that point economically,

00:35:17.800 --> 00:35:24.040
[Amit Varma]: what is our trajectory? How are we sort of growing? How are we doing? And then the implications

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:26.080
[Amit Varma]: of the 2008 financial crisis?

00:35:26.080 --> 00:35:32.160
[Guest]: Yes, this is the other thing, you know, which first time voters either not aware or they've

00:35:32.160 --> 00:35:37.320
[Guest]: completely forgotten, which is that the India and the Indian economy, you know, in the in

00:35:37.320 --> 00:35:44.240
[Guest]: the before 2008 was so different from what it is today. You know, the Tata's are buying,

00:35:44.240 --> 00:35:51.520
[Guest]: you know, chorus and JLR, Jaguar, Land Rover, and even small, I mean, they're big companies,

00:35:51.520 --> 00:35:56.000
[Guest]: but even small Indian companies, midsize Indian companies were going and acquiring companies

00:35:56.000 --> 00:36:02.240
[Guest]: overseas, businesses overseas, there was so much exuberance. You'd recall, if you were

00:36:02.240 --> 00:36:08.160
[Guest]: in a job at that point, the kind of increments we were getting, the kind of, you know, job

00:36:08.160 --> 00:36:15.640
[Guest]: opportunities that are coming up. India was growing at 8.8%, three years consecutively

00:36:15.640 --> 00:36:22.080
[Guest]: before 2008, India grew at 8.8%, which is unprecedented in the history of independent

00:36:22.080 --> 00:36:28.200
[Guest]: India. A lot of this was because the world economy was booming, the cost of money was

00:36:28.200 --> 00:36:32.080
[Guest]: very low, international interest rates were very low. And when you have very low interest

00:36:32.080 --> 00:36:36.080
[Guest]: rates, if you can borrow money at a very low price, you know, interest rates of like 1%

00:36:36.080 --> 00:36:41.080
[Guest]: or nearly 0%, what are you going to do, you're going to bet with that money, you know, because

00:36:41.080 --> 00:36:48.720
[Guest]: your cost of money is so low, your risk taking ability goes up. And internationally investors

00:36:48.720 --> 00:36:53.240
[Guest]: were looking for where to put their money so that they could get high returns. And they

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:58.120
[Guest]: discovered emerging markets and among emerging markets, this economy called India that had

00:36:58.120 --> 00:37:04.000
[Guest]: started with economic reforms. And there was a lot of promise that, you know, those economic

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:10.040
[Guest]: reforms will be carried further. And India was going to have this huge demographic dividend

00:37:10.040 --> 00:37:15.440
[Guest]: because a large proportion of the population was going to be young and therefore, you know,

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:19.920
[Guest]: earning jobs, earning incomes, and therefore spending. So India was a very attractive market

00:37:19.920 --> 00:37:24.360
[Guest]: at that point in time. That's how the potential was. And everything seemed right. The government

00:37:24.360 --> 00:37:32.080
[Guest]: was headed by an economist, you know, Dr. Manmohan Singh, was a very celebrated political

00:37:32.080 --> 00:37:36.360
[Guest]: leader. The finance minister was Peter Damram. Again, he's, you know, he has this reputation

00:37:36.360 --> 00:37:43.280
[Guest]: internationally of being a darling of investors. He had in the reforms era, in the 1990s, presented

00:37:43.280 --> 00:37:48.600
[Guest]: what is called a dream budget, where he reduced income taxes so drastically that the, you

00:37:48.600 --> 00:37:53.240
[Guest]: know, the collection of income taxes increased. It was a stark contrast to the, you know,

00:37:53.240 --> 00:37:58.880
[Guest]: marginal rate of 90% during Mrs. Indira Gandhi's time. And that was a very big reform. In fact,

00:37:58.880 --> 00:38:06.400
[Guest]: the rationalization of income taxes, he had in the 1990s, you know, taken off a whole

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:12.280
[Guest]: lot of, he had liberalized trade a lot. So he came with excellent credentials. And between

00:38:12.280 --> 00:38:20.440
[Guest]: 2005 and 2007, people have forgotten this, but he had reduced the fiscal deficit so drastically,

00:38:20.440 --> 00:38:26.480
[Guest]: not by cutting expenditure so much, more by raising more money through taxes, you know,

00:38:26.480 --> 00:38:31.440
[Guest]: because the economy was growing so well that people were paying more taxes. And, you know,

00:38:31.440 --> 00:38:36.680
[Guest]: the tax system at that time was not as coercive as it started becoming from the era of Pranam

00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:44.080
[Guest]: Mukherjee when this whole tax terrorism thing came up. And the income tax to GDP ratio that

00:38:44.080 --> 00:38:51.080
[Guest]: was achieved in 2007 has not been achieved even till today, you know, that high. And

00:38:51.080 --> 00:38:58.680
[Guest]: so, you know, fiscally, the macroeconomic parameters looked very good. The economy looked

00:38:58.680 --> 00:39:03.960
[Guest]: very attractive and therefore a lot of foreign investment began to come in. When the foreigners

00:39:03.960 --> 00:39:10.480
[Guest]: discovered India and started investing here, the local, you know, companies also figured

00:39:10.480 --> 00:39:15.360
[Guest]: that this was the time to, you know, take risk. This was the time to expand because

00:39:15.360 --> 00:39:19.120
[Guest]: India has so much problems. If the foreigners think we are a great economy, then we really,

00:39:19.120 --> 00:39:24.440
[Guest]: really must be a great economy. And, you know, a whole lot of investments started taking

00:39:24.440 --> 00:39:29.240
[Guest]: place. So yeah, the economy was booming, exports were doing very well because world demand

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:36.000
[Guest]: for exports was quite robust. Investments were doing very well and manufacturing was

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:42.680
[Guest]: doing much better than it is, you know, it has ever. Now, this was the state of the economy,

00:39:42.680 --> 00:39:48.280
[Guest]: you know, a global boom and within that an Indian boom when the global financial crisis

00:39:48.280 --> 00:39:58.000
[Guest]: happened. The global financial crisis sort of disrupted this whole exuberance that India

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:03.320
[Guest]: was seeing. Sorry, I forgot to mention, which I explained in the book, which is that, you

00:40:03.320 --> 00:40:07.920
[Guest]: know, when the cities were experiencing this boom because of all these investments, foreigners

00:40:07.920 --> 00:40:12.960
[Guest]: coming in, a lot of hiring taking place, company expanding, getting into new businesses. What

00:40:12.960 --> 00:40:21.680
[Guest]: that did was that, you know, the city's needs for support staff, you know, sort of grew.

00:40:21.680 --> 00:40:27.160
[Guest]: They needed new malls, they needed a lot more drivers, they needed a lot more assistance.

00:40:27.160 --> 00:40:32.520
[Guest]: And these requirements were supplied by the rural area. So a lot of people began to come

00:40:32.520 --> 00:40:39.760
[Guest]: from rural India to the cities, you know, for these jobs. And that's how the gains of

00:40:39.760 --> 00:40:46.520
[Guest]: this boom, you know, was sort of shared with the rural areas as well. And once when the

00:40:46.520 --> 00:40:53.360
[Guest]: global financial crisis disrupts this, then it was quite serious and all kinds of changes

00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:57.800
[Guest]: happen. You know, that's how the book begins. All kinds of changes happen in the economy

00:40:57.800 --> 00:41:03.760
[Guest]: directly because of the crisis, but also indirectly because of the way Indian policy responds

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:11.400
[Guest]: to that crisis. And initially those are positive dynamics. And, you know, eventually because

00:41:11.400 --> 00:41:17.960
[Guest]: of policy errors, things begin to go haywire and the Indian economy actually suffers more

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:26.080
[Guest]: than it would have if policy decisions were better. So, yeah, so that's how the book begins.

00:41:26.080 --> 00:41:33.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And you talk about sort of the first period after 2008, where the Indian policymakers

00:41:33.200 --> 00:41:37.680
[Amit Varma]: led by Chidambaram and Montek Singhaluwalia are very precise about what they need to do.

00:41:37.680 --> 00:41:41.680
[Amit Varma]: To quote from your book, quote, Chidambaram's instructions to the crisis managers at the

00:41:41.680 --> 00:41:46.280
[Amit Varma]: RBI and the government were precise. He wanted measures that could ensure three objectives,

00:41:46.280 --> 00:41:51.360
[Amit Varma]: enough liquidity in the market, no run on banks, and no bank collapses resulting from

00:41:51.360 --> 00:41:56.680
[Amit Varma]: asset liability mismatch, stop quote. And the response of all the policymakers is again

00:41:56.680 --> 00:42:00.680
[Amit Varma]: very considered, very precise, not looking at political considerations, just trying to

00:42:00.680 --> 00:42:06.960
[Amit Varma]: handle the crisis and get India out of there. And, and they kind of succeed in doing that.

00:42:06.960 --> 00:42:11.760
[Amit Varma]: And is this sort of, you know, in all the years that as an economic journalist, you've

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:17.680
[Amit Varma]: been covering government, is this an aberration? Or is this something that can sort of happen

00:42:17.680 --> 00:42:23.320
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, outside of politics, economic decision makers continuously keep making the

00:42:23.320 --> 00:42:24.320
[Amit Varma]: right decisions?

00:42:24.320 --> 00:42:29.960
[Guest]: No, it's, it's an aberration. And it happens only when there's a crisis. What happens is

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:37.360
[Guest]: that, you know, in 2008, nobody wanted a repeat of 1991. And therefore, you know, just like

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:41.960
[Guest]: in 1991, they had given a free hand, finally, you know, after things go horribly wrong in

00:42:41.960 --> 00:42:48.280
[Guest]: the IMF lays down conditions. Finally, in 1991, they gave a free hand to the economists.

00:42:48.280 --> 00:42:52.720
[Guest]: Same thing happens in 2008, that, you know, because there's a crisis, and you're seeing

00:42:52.720 --> 00:42:57.600
[Guest]: globally how severe the crisis is, you don't know how exposed you are to that. And you

00:42:57.600 --> 00:43:02.280
[Guest]: don't know how much you're going to suffer because of that at that point in time. You're

00:43:02.280 --> 00:43:06.960
[Guest]: so scared that you let the, you know, economists take the right decisions, because you don't

00:43:06.960 --> 00:43:12.880
[Guest]: want a repeat of 1991. And I think that's what happened in 2008, the economists actually

00:43:12.880 --> 00:43:18.860
[Guest]: got a free hand. And politicians let them do what was needed to be done, because nobody

00:43:18.860 --> 00:43:22.800
[Guest]: wanted to repeat. Also, I think it helped at that point in time that the key people

00:43:22.800 --> 00:43:28.200
[Guest]: involved, you know, like, if you're going to have Manmohan Singh as your prime minister,

00:43:28.200 --> 00:43:33.080
[Guest]: he understands these things a lot more than a political prime minister would have. And

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:38.680
[Guest]: therefore he, you know, gave the economists a free hand. Same with Chidambaram. Chidambaram

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:43.320
[Guest]: had seen, you know, the aftermath of the 1991. Also, we must not forget, this is not there

00:43:43.320 --> 00:43:49.240
[Guest]: in my book, but it can be seen in the book written by Dr. Reddy. His memoir is that,

00:43:49.240 --> 00:43:56.680
[Guest]: you know, Dr. Reddy tries to caution P. Chidambaram in the run up to 2008, many times of, you

00:43:56.680 --> 00:44:01.000
[Guest]: know, how the economy is overheating, and there's this international imbalances are

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:06.760
[Guest]: growing, and Chidambaram is not so receptive to it. I think that may have also been a thing

00:44:06.760 --> 00:44:10.440
[Guest]: that you know, he may, it may have weighed on him that he had not listened to Reddy until

00:44:10.440 --> 00:44:15.920
[Guest]: 2008 and Reddy was right, there is this crisis that breaks. And therefore, he's now a little

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:20.640
[Guest]: more careful and willing to listen to economists. I'm speculating over here, this might be also,

00:44:20.640 --> 00:44:21.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, one factor.

00:44:21.640 --> 00:44:25.440
[Amit Varma]: No, and in a sense, your book and what I like about your book is that it's not just a book

00:44:25.440 --> 00:44:30.440
[Amit Varma]: of economics. It's also a lot of human drama in there. I mean, at the surface level, of

00:44:30.440 --> 00:44:34.800
[Amit Varma]: course, it's about how politics impacts economics, but there's also a lot of human drama between

00:44:34.800 --> 00:44:39.160
[Amit Varma]: all these different characters. And, you know, the internal dynamics that's going on, which

00:44:39.160 --> 00:44:42.880
[Amit Varma]: was like, very fascinating to me, I thought, you know, you know, Shakespeare could pick

00:44:42.880 --> 00:44:46.520
[Amit Varma]: up the book and find things in this, which would, you know, remind him of King Lear,

00:44:46.520 --> 00:44:47.520
[Amit Varma]: for example.

00:44:47.520 --> 00:44:53.560
[Guest]: Yeah, because, you know, as a journalist, you're kind of an insider, outsider, kind

00:44:53.560 --> 00:44:59.400
[Guest]: of, you know, you're, you're often watching a whole lot of things. And you're seeing things

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:03.160
[Guest]: that, you know, people are doing and you're, you're seeing that they're driven by things

00:45:03.160 --> 00:45:08.160
[Guest]: other than, you know, policy, somebody's pushing for something only because he's looking at

00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:12.640
[Guest]: a career, you know, sinecure post retirement. So as a journalist, you're always watching

00:45:12.640 --> 00:45:17.120
[Guest]: these, these things, and sometimes they become more important than other considerations when

00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:18.640
[Amit Varma]: policy decisions have to be taken.

00:45:18.640 --> 00:45:22.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, the drama is pretty Shakespearean. I mean, you got King Lear, Macbeth, Comedy

00:45:22.760 --> 00:45:26.880
[Amit Varma]: of Errors, all of that, you know, you've given an excellent account in your first chapter,

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:31.840
[Amit Varma]: the shock of how our policymakers responded to that. But for me, where the book really

00:45:31.840 --> 00:45:37.240
[Amit Varma]: gets fascinating is from the combination of the two seminal events which change everything

00:45:37.240 --> 00:45:42.760
[Amit Varma]: and which are not events you would expect to disrupt an economy to the scale that it

00:45:42.760 --> 00:45:49.560
[Amit Varma]: did. And the first of those, interestingly, is the 2008 terrorist attacks. What happened?

00:45:49.560 --> 00:45:57.080
[Guest]: Yes, so, so I think that sort of determined the course of the decade, a lot more than

00:45:57.080 --> 00:46:03.960
[Guest]: anything else to do with politics or economics or, you know, conscious decision making. Then

00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:10.800
[Guest]: the terror attack happened. Home Minister in charge had to resign. So, you know, there

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:14.480
[Guest]: was a whole controversy, if you recall about, you know, how many times he was changing his

00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:20.880
[Guest]: outfit and all that. And there was a lot of noise by the opposition and he, he resigned.

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:25.480
[Guest]: Now when he resigned, Peter Dumbrum is brought in as the Home Minister, and this is barely

00:46:25.480 --> 00:46:30.680
[Guest]: I think a month and a half after the global financial crisis breaks. And so Peter Dumbrum

00:46:30.680 --> 00:46:36.720
[Guest]: gives up on finance ministry. So there's a vacancy in the finance ministry. Now, so what

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:40.680
[Guest]: Manmohan Singh decides is that he's going to, you know, take the additional charge for

00:46:40.680 --> 00:46:44.600
[Guest]: the finance ministry and everybody in the finance ministry and everybody in the economy

00:46:44.600 --> 00:46:49.080
[Guest]: as a whole, you know, industrialists and all, they're all very excited because here's the

00:46:49.080 --> 00:46:53.640
[Guest]: person you know, who was the most important character in the 1991 reforms, and he's now

00:46:53.640 --> 00:46:58.640
[Guest]: the finance minister apart from being the Prime Minister. And, you know, so we are going

00:46:58.640 --> 00:47:05.480
[Guest]: to resume the 1991 reforms kind of thing. But that turns out to be a very temporary

00:47:05.480 --> 00:47:15.680
[Guest]: thing because in January, unexpectedly, he has to go in for a coronary bypass. And Chidambaram

00:47:15.680 --> 00:47:21.200
[Guest]: tells me as I write in the book that nobody knew about this. Chidambaram heard of this,

00:47:21.200 --> 00:47:25.840
[Guest]: you know, when Dr. Singh was being, you know, taken to AIMS and was on the way, that's when

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:31.120
[Guest]: the Home Minister finds out about it. So it's very, something very unexpected. Now, when

00:47:31.120 --> 00:47:36.840
[Guest]: the Prime Minister becomes indisposed for something like this, there is a lot of, you

00:47:36.840 --> 00:47:43.920
[Guest]: know, standard procedures that sort of have to be followed. And part of that is that you

00:47:43.920 --> 00:47:52.120
[Guest]: need a new finance minister. Now, in Lutyens Delhi, the feeling amongst everybody is that,

00:47:52.120 --> 00:47:58.480
[Guest]: you know, the additional charge will pass on from Manmohan Singh to Peter Chidambaram

00:47:58.480 --> 00:48:04.720
[Guest]: because even as Home Minister, he was assisting a little bit. He was assisting Manmohan Singh,

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:10.080
[Guest]: you know, in his finance ministry duties. Mainly, you know, every minister has to respond

00:48:10.080 --> 00:48:16.080
[Guest]: to questions in Parliament and ministers, we don't, you know, average people don't take

00:48:16.080 --> 00:48:19.680
[Guest]: that that seriously. But for the minister, that's very important. Every minister takes

00:48:19.680 --> 00:48:22.840
[Guest]: his parliamentary questions very, very seriously. It's the most important thing according to

00:48:22.840 --> 00:48:30.440
[Guest]: them that they do. And for that, Peter Chidambaram was assisting the Prime Minister and officials

00:48:30.440 --> 00:48:36.240
[Guest]: used to go to him in his Home Ministry office for briefing, etc. And the other thing was

00:48:36.240 --> 00:48:44.880
[Guest]: that election was coming and was approaching and therefore an interim budget had to be

00:48:44.880 --> 00:48:51.320
[Guest]: placed in Parliament and there were preparations on for the interim budget. And under instructions

00:48:51.320 --> 00:48:55.960
[Guest]: from Manmohan Singh, the interim budget meetings of finance ministry officials were being taken

00:48:55.960 --> 00:49:02.480
[Guest]: by Peter Chidambaram in his Home Ministry office. And therefore, you know, when secretaries

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:05.600
[Guest]: to Government of India are going to him and discussing with him what needs to be done

00:49:05.600 --> 00:49:10.760
[Guest]: in the interim budget, the impression in Lutyens Delhi is that, you know, now that the Prime

00:49:10.760 --> 00:49:15.240
[Guest]: Minister can no longer hold charge and he's going to be hospitalized, etc. in this post

00:49:15.240 --> 00:49:19.200
[Guest]: and therefore, you know, the charge will pass on to Peter Chidambaram. And so, you know,

00:49:19.200 --> 00:49:24.160
[Guest]: there's this meeting that I describe in the book, you know, where they've all had this

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:27.280
[Guest]: meeting with Peter Chidambaram in his Home Ministry office. And, you know, they're all

00:49:27.280 --> 00:49:32.520
[Guest]: discussing on the way walking that, you know, how he's going to now be the only person in

00:49:32.520 --> 00:49:37.840
[Guest]: history of India to hold Home Ministry and Finance Ministry charge, two portfolios that

00:49:37.840 --> 00:49:44.600
[Guest]: give you disproportionate control in Government of India. And by the time they return to their

00:49:44.600 --> 00:49:49.200
[Guest]: chamber and, you know, this particular official, the television is switched on and, you know,

00:49:49.200 --> 00:49:53.480
[Guest]: he started to find that the press communique from the President House says that additional

00:49:53.480 --> 00:49:58.760
[Guest]: charge for Finance Ministry has been given to Pranam Mukherjee. And nobody could have

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:05.080
[Guest]: guessed that. And, you know, Pranam Mukherjee is given additional charge, but the press

00:50:05.080 --> 00:50:09.680
[Guest]: communique quite clearly says it is only for as long as Manmohan Singh is indisposed. But

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:16.080
[Guest]: once Manmohan Singh returns to office in March, which is just a little short of when elections

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:20.920
[Guest]: are announced, Pranam Mukherjee does not give up on the additional charge. He holds on to

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:27.120
[Guest]: that charge. Now, what is the politics behind it? I only speculate in my book. I don't know.

00:50:27.120 --> 00:50:31.800
[Guest]: But nobody expects at that point in time for this government to get voted back to power.

00:50:31.800 --> 00:50:36.880
[Guest]: And once the elections happen, this government is voted back to power. And interestingly,

00:50:36.880 --> 00:50:43.000
[Guest]: you know, they retain Pranam Mukherjee as the Finance Minister. And P. Chidambaram tells

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:49.520
[Guest]: me, you know, and I put that in the book, that Manmohan Singh was very clear and very

00:50:49.520 --> 00:50:56.600
[Guest]: clearly had told P. Chidambaram that he intended to hold the finance portfolio. He had plans

00:50:56.600 --> 00:51:03.120
[Guest]: for the economy and for economic policy. And he intended to hold that portfolio. That portfolio

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:09.440
[Guest]: passes on to Pranam Mukherjee. And until 2012, you know, Pranam Mukherjee is the Finance

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:14.120
[Guest]: Minister. Now, this is an outcome of first, the Mumbai terror attacks. Secondly, the bypass

00:51:14.120 --> 00:51:19.800
[Guest]: surgery that Manmohan Singh goes into. And, you know, some politics that goes on where

00:51:19.800 --> 00:51:25.200
[Guest]: this portfolio goes to Pranam Mukherjee. But, you know, when we look at between the time,

00:51:25.200 --> 00:51:29.880
[Guest]: the three and a half years, Pranam Mukherjee has been the Finance Minister, he takes so

00:51:29.880 --> 00:51:37.920
[Guest]: many decisions that have such a, you know, overbearing, disproportional impact on the

00:51:37.920 --> 00:51:43.560
[Guest]: economic policy and therefore the economy in this decade. And he's in that position

00:51:43.560 --> 00:51:49.480
[Guest]: to make that influence, despite not the Prime Minister's first choice. So, you know, that's

00:51:49.480 --> 00:51:55.760
[Guest]: what I mean when I say that things, you know, don't always go like, you know, how we plan

00:51:55.760 --> 00:52:00.560
[Amit Varma]: and the rule of chance, etc. Yeah. And the interesting thing about Mukherjee

00:52:00.560 --> 00:52:06.200
[Amit Varma]: is that even though he's completely on top of politics, you know, he's known as a Mooran

00:52:06.200 --> 00:52:10.200
[Amit Varma]: shaker and someone who's can, you know, negotiate with all the parties and get things done.

00:52:10.200 --> 00:52:13.720
[Amit Varma]: When it comes to economics, it's completely the other way around. As you point out, he'd

00:52:13.720 --> 00:52:17.720
[Amit Varma]: held the finance portfolio 24 years earlier. If I remember correctly, when Indira Gandhi

00:52:17.720 --> 00:52:23.440
[Amit Varma]: was assassinated, he was Finance Minister. And you quote a secretary in his department

00:52:23.440 --> 00:52:28.480
[Amit Varma]: saying, quote, he was in the first few months a bit lost. The world had changed. He had

00:52:28.480 --> 00:52:34.200
[Amit Varma]: not changed. Stop quote. And you elaborate on this when you say, and now I'll quote you,

00:52:34.200 --> 00:52:39.240
[Amit Varma]: finance and economics has changed. Since then, the economy had been liberalized, it had changed

00:52:39.240 --> 00:52:43.840
[Amit Varma]: structurally and fundamentally, the work culture and mindsets in the ministry had changed to

00:52:43.840 --> 00:52:49.960
[Amit Varma]: Mukherjee, though still seem to swear by the socialist era ideology that had long been

00:52:49.960 --> 00:52:55.120
[Amit Varma]: retired. His approach and instinct was still defined by an abiding faith in the jaded judicious

00:52:55.120 --> 00:53:00.680
[Amit Varma]: doctrine. The new finance minister was not as conversant with the new economic order

00:53:00.680 --> 00:53:05.760
[Amit Varma]: as his post liberalization predecessors were. Mukherjee soon earned a reputation for being

00:53:05.760 --> 00:53:10.560
[Amit Varma]: old school and being out of tune with global economic affairs, stop quote. And what kind

00:53:10.560 --> 00:53:15.560
[Amit Varma]: of adds to this, which is very intriguing, because this is again, you know, a dynamic

00:53:15.560 --> 00:53:21.840
[Amit Varma]: that has obviously come about because of politics is that he is disinclined to listen to anything

00:53:21.840 --> 00:53:27.360
[Amit Varma]: his Prime Minister, Manmohan says, you know, and part of this might well be because when

00:53:27.360 --> 00:53:31.480
[Amit Varma]: he was finance minister under Indira Gandhi, he had appointed Manmohan as a governor of

00:53:31.480 --> 00:53:37.240
[Amit Varma]: the RBI. So now the tables are almost kind of reversed. But part of it is surely because

00:53:37.240 --> 00:53:43.800
[Amit Varma]: of this increasing sort of ambiguity about who is really in charge here. Is it Manmohan

00:53:43.800 --> 00:53:50.360
[Guest]: Singh or is it Sonia Gandhi? So, yeah, the second chapter is actually about all of this.

00:53:50.360 --> 00:53:58.480
[Guest]: And I do say in this chapter that, you know, Pranam Mukherjee represents everything ideologically

00:53:58.480 --> 00:54:04.440
[Guest]: and otherwise that Manmohan Singh had taken apart in 1991 through his reforms. Manmohan

00:54:04.440 --> 00:54:09.880
[Guest]: Singh represents what happened in 1991. But, you know, Pranam Mukherjee represents what

00:54:09.880 --> 00:54:15.040
[Guest]: it was that Manmohan Singh had taken apart. And Pranam Mukherjee is not able to update

00:54:15.040 --> 00:54:19.840
[Guest]: his ways to post 1991. And therefore, when once he's back in the finance ministry, what

00:54:19.840 --> 00:54:26.520
[Guest]: he does, he tries to recreate a pre 1991, you know, economic policy regime. And this

00:54:26.520 --> 00:54:32.040
[Guest]: is not just me saying this, you know, Pranam Mukherjee in his memoirs a couple of times

00:54:32.040 --> 00:54:38.240
[Guest]: says that his and Manmohan Singh's ideologies were poles apart. They could never agree on

00:54:38.240 --> 00:54:47.640
[Guest]: their economic ideology. And Peter Dumbrin also tells me the same thing. And except that,

00:54:47.640 --> 00:54:53.760
[Guest]: you know, they are both very graceful in the way they negotiate their differences, Manmohan

00:54:53.760 --> 00:54:59.200
[Guest]: Singh and Pranam Mukherjee. And this, you know, I hear from everybody in the bureaucracy

00:54:59.200 --> 00:55:04.760
[Guest]: and cabinet colleagues of the two of them where they say that, yes, they both ideologically

00:55:04.760 --> 00:55:12.120
[Guest]: disagree completely, but they don't disrespect each other. There is a point by when their

00:55:12.120 --> 00:55:17.840
[Guest]: differences are so deep and so non-negotiable. And I think I wouldn't say this is because

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:23.320
[Guest]: of Sonia Gandhi. What I bring out in the book, I think it is because of Manmohan Singh's

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:31.320
[Guest]: personality. It never comes to a point where Manmohan Singh tells Pranam Mukherjee, listen,

00:55:31.320 --> 00:55:34.480
[Guest]: you disagree with what I think should be done, but I still want you to do this. I'm your

00:55:34.480 --> 00:55:39.640
[Guest]: prime minister. He'd never says that. And I really wish he could have done something

00:55:39.640 --> 00:55:44.320
[Guest]: like that because after all, he's a prime minister. I think it is his personality, you

00:55:44.320 --> 00:55:49.560
[Guest]: know, where he sort of doesn't do that. Such as, you know, one of the examples I give is

00:55:49.560 --> 00:55:55.880
[Guest]: infamous Vodafone retrospective taxation provision where the government of India loses the case

00:55:55.880 --> 00:56:01.440
[Guest]: in the Supreme Court and yet Pranam Mukherjee brings in, you know, a legal provision overturning

00:56:01.440 --> 00:56:09.280
[Guest]: that and, you know, slaps this tax bill on to Vodafone capital gains. Before he took

00:56:09.280 --> 00:56:13.400
[Guest]: that decision, he discusses this, you know, in the core committee of the Congress where

00:56:13.400 --> 00:56:18.240
[Guest]: there's the prime minister and a whole lot of other ministers, each one of them. And

00:56:18.240 --> 00:56:23.040
[Guest]: he himself writes this in his book, in his memoir, that even Sonia Gandhi told him not

00:56:23.040 --> 00:56:26.320
[Guest]: to do it. Manmohan Singh explained to him why it was not the right thing to do, but

00:56:26.320 --> 00:56:31.840
[Guest]: he still went ahead, you know, not listening to them. He still went ahead and he did it.

00:56:31.840 --> 00:56:37.520
[Guest]: And I think that's the thing. Pranam Mukherjee was just this personality in the UPA2 government

00:56:37.520 --> 00:56:43.000
[Guest]: who would just do what he wanted to do. Most of what he wanted to do was, you know, how

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:48.160
[Guest]: decisions were taken in pre-liberalization India, because that's, you know, those were

00:56:48.160 --> 00:56:54.520
[Guest]: his formative years. He was refusing to tune himself to the post 1991 economy. And at no

00:56:54.520 --> 00:56:58.840
[Guest]: point does the prime minister tell him that, you know, I'm advising you to do what I'm

00:56:58.840 --> 00:57:03.120
[Guest]: saying. So he kind of, you know, has this free hand and I describe in the book that

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:07.280
[Guest]: it does reach a point where there's no communication between the two of them. And finance minister's

00:57:07.280 --> 00:57:12.280
[Guest]: office and the prime minister's office communicate with each other only through messengers. There's

00:57:12.280 --> 00:57:16.360
[Guest]: an example also I give there of a particular decision that has to be taken and how, you

00:57:16.360 --> 00:57:20.280
[Guest]: know, they go about, the prime minister goes about, you know, getting Pranam Mukherjee

00:57:20.280 --> 00:57:27.560
[Guest]: to finally, you know, sign on the file. But so, so, you know, your prime minister and

00:57:27.560 --> 00:57:31.840
[Guest]: your finance minister is not even talking to each other at a time when the economy sort

00:57:31.840 --> 00:57:37.560
[Guest]: of recovering from a very severe shock. The finance minister's ideologically driven to

00:57:37.560 --> 00:57:40.800
[Guest]: do everything that he should not be doing, you know, he's doing everything opposite of

00:57:40.800 --> 00:57:47.840
[Guest]: what is required in the economy. Can you imagine, you know, the kind of policy chaos that goes

00:57:47.840 --> 00:57:52.920
[Guest]: on in such a government and the price we are paying of it even today.

00:57:52.920 --> 00:57:57.240
[Amit Varma]: So I'll quote from your book again about the impact of his years. At one point, you write,

00:57:57.240 --> 00:58:02.040
[Amit Varma]: within 24 months of Mukherjee's entry into the finance ministry, the GDP growth rate

00:58:02.040 --> 00:58:12.200
[Amit Varma]: crashed from 8.9% in 2010-11 to 5.5% in 2012-13. And elsewhere, you write, before Mukherjee's

00:58:12.200 --> 00:58:15.720
[Amit Varma]: appointment as finance minister, India was on the verge of being christened a miracle

00:58:15.720 --> 00:58:20.780
[Amit Varma]: economy. By the time Mukherjee exited, large fiscal deficits and a high net international

00:58:20.780 --> 00:58:25.960
[Amit Varma]: debt position had made the country vulnerable to global financial shocks and terms of trade

00:58:25.960 --> 00:58:31.600
[Amit Varma]: shocks. Stop quote. You know, sum up for me, what are the different things he did, which

00:58:31.600 --> 00:58:35.760
[Amit Varma]: obviously Manmohan and Chidambaram would have done differently? What are the kind of policy

00:58:35.760 --> 00:58:40.640
[Amit Varma]: decisions which went into play, which made all of this happen?

00:58:40.640 --> 00:58:50.080
[Guest]: So, broadly along two lines, one was his whole approach to tax policy and, you know, sectoral

00:58:50.080 --> 00:58:56.520
[Guest]: policies that dampened the investment mood, the investor's mood. If you recall, the whole

00:58:56.520 --> 00:59:03.680
[Guest]: Vodafone thing was a huge embarrassment for India as an economy in the global investor

00:59:03.680 --> 00:59:09.720
[Guest]: community. India was, you know, not seen as a good investment destination after that.

00:59:09.720 --> 00:59:14.120
[Guest]: Secondly, you know, there were a lot of reforms that as finance minister, he was in charge

00:59:14.120 --> 00:59:20.200
[Guest]: of that he just did not push through. Most important of which is the GST. Here is a politician

00:59:20.200 --> 00:59:27.520
[Guest]: known to create consensus and build bridges with the opposition and push legislation through.

00:59:27.520 --> 00:59:32.880
[Guest]: If you recall, you know, he was a troubleshooter, so-called, of the government. And for one

00:59:32.880 --> 00:59:38.600
[Guest]: legislation, you know, the constitution amendment to introduce the GST, that falls in the purview

00:59:38.600 --> 00:59:44.560
[Guest]: of his own ministry. For nearly three years, the standing committee on finance headed by

00:59:44.560 --> 00:59:50.440
[Guest]: Yashwant Sinha did not even prepare its report. So, you know, that's a procedural step. Unless

00:59:50.440 --> 00:59:55.480
[Guest]: the standing committee gives its report, you cannot proceed with what you need to do to,

00:59:55.480 --> 01:00:01.680
[Guest]: you know, move the constitution amendment bill to introduce GST. How did he not, you

01:00:01.680 --> 01:00:08.760
[Guest]: know, persuade Yashwant Sinha to speed up the process of giving his committee report?

01:00:08.760 --> 01:00:13.640
[Guest]: So, you know, those are the steps in terms of the reform steps that needed to be taken.

01:00:13.640 --> 01:00:17.920
[Guest]: There are many other such examples that I give in the book.

01:00:17.920 --> 01:00:22.160
[Amit Varma]: You point out how Dr. Arvind Virmani had actually given a whole list of reforms which needed

01:00:22.160 --> 01:00:27.160
[Amit Varma]: to be carried out, which Manmohan and Chidambaram were on board with, but Mukherjee just completely

01:00:27.160 --> 01:00:32.360
[Amit Varma]: ghosted him as, you know, millennials would say. And, you know, Dr. Virmani was telling

01:00:32.360 --> 01:00:35.320
[Guest]: me, which I, you know, I quote him in the book is that, you know, he was earlier the

01:00:35.320 --> 01:00:44.240
[Guest]: chief economic advisor and then he's appointed as India's representative at the IMF in Washington.

01:00:44.240 --> 01:00:47.440
[Guest]: And so once a year, every year, he used to come down to India and, you know, as part

01:00:47.440 --> 01:00:51.520
[Guest]: of protocol, he used to meet the finance minister and, you know, the chief economic advisor

01:00:51.520 --> 01:00:56.040
[Guest]: and all that. And in his meetings with the finance minister, Pranam Mukherjee, he tries

01:00:56.040 --> 01:01:00.040
[Guest]: to tell the finance minister that these are reforms that you need to do. And, you know,

01:01:00.040 --> 01:01:03.640
[Guest]: this is what you need to do with your fiscal policy. And because you're not doing your

01:01:03.640 --> 01:01:08.120
[Guest]: fiscal policy the way it needs to be, it is impacting the monetary policy. And, you know,

01:01:08.120 --> 01:01:14.200
[Guest]: the fiscal policy, monetary policy combination is just going haywire. So, Pranam Mukherjee

01:01:14.200 --> 01:01:18.920
[Guest]: tells him that, listen, you know, right now, let this be, but when you come, you know,

01:01:18.920 --> 01:01:23.520
[Guest]: just before the next budget, you come back and you tell me and in the coming budget,

01:01:23.520 --> 01:01:29.920
[Guest]: I, you know, we will do this, we will do what you're saying. So, Arvind Mani plans a special

01:01:29.920 --> 01:01:35.120
[Guest]: trip to India from Washington to come and meet Pranam Mukherjee in Delhi before budget

01:01:35.120 --> 01:01:40.520
[Guest]: preparations start in North Block to brief him on what needs to be done. And when he

01:01:40.520 --> 01:01:46.160
[Guest]: comes back in this particular trip to explain to him and, you know, to brief him on what

01:01:46.160 --> 01:01:52.000
[Guest]: needs to be done on economic policy and fiscal policy, et cetera, reforms. But he failed

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:57.040
[Guest]: to get an appointment, you know, from the finance minister's office. And he is forced

01:01:57.040 --> 01:02:03.080
[Guest]: to return to Washington. You know, the trip is wasted because the finance minister's office

01:02:03.080 --> 01:02:08.080
[Guest]: does not give him an appointment to meet Pranam Mukherjee. And all these reforms that he has

01:02:08.080 --> 01:02:15.600
[Guest]: recommended don't take place. GST does not make much progress because the standing committee

01:02:15.600 --> 01:02:21.160
[Guest]: is sitting on its report. It's headed by Ashwant Sinha. And on top of that, all these decisions

01:02:21.160 --> 01:02:26.720
[Guest]: are getting taken, you know, where you're after a private sector company, a Vodafone,

01:02:26.720 --> 01:02:31.240
[Guest]: you know, wins a case against you in the Supreme Court and you bring, you know, legislative

01:02:31.240 --> 01:02:38.440
[Guest]: changes to, you know, sort of force them to do what you want to do. And that's completely

01:02:38.440 --> 01:02:43.680
[Guest]: destroying India's reputation internationally as an investment destination. And you're also

01:02:43.680 --> 01:02:49.840
[Guest]: following this policy of, you know, just sort of injecting so much money into the economy.

01:02:49.840 --> 01:02:54.160
[Guest]: Again, going completely against the advice you have received from the economists in the

01:02:54.160 --> 01:03:00.000
[Guest]: government, you're not rolling the part of the response measures that were designed by

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:04.400
[Guest]: the economists, you know, because of which Indian economy did not completely collapse

01:03:04.400 --> 01:03:09.240
[Guest]: after the global financial crisis. Part of that was this whole fiscal stimulus spending

01:03:09.240 --> 01:03:13.920
[Guest]: that needed to be done. Now, it is very clear in their heads and in their proposals that

01:03:13.920 --> 01:03:19.240
[Guest]: this was all very temporary measures. You cannot give this stimulus year after year,

01:03:19.240 --> 01:03:26.600
[Guest]: you know, unendingly. But Pranab Mukherjee refuses to, you know, roll back that stimulus.

01:03:26.600 --> 01:03:31.800
[Guest]: It just goes on and on and on. And the fiscal deficit keeps climbing. It reaches a point

01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:38.360
[Guest]: where, you know, the fiscal deficit is 6% for the central government. And, you know,

01:03:38.360 --> 01:03:42.440
[Guest]: that has implications in the real economy, that has implications for monetary policy.

01:03:42.440 --> 01:03:49.680
[Guest]: And I also described how the RBI governor comes to Delhi for meetings before his monetary

01:03:49.680 --> 01:03:55.920
[Guest]: policy announcements to meet the finance minister. And in these meetings, the finance minister

01:03:55.920 --> 01:04:02.760
[Guest]: never says anything, but his whole team of officials, you know, keep forcing the RBI

01:04:02.760 --> 01:04:08.040
[Guest]: governor to, you know, make changes in the monetary policy, saying that there's nothing

01:04:08.040 --> 01:04:12.520
[Guest]: we can do from here, you know, in North Block about fiscal policy and whatever that needs

01:04:12.520 --> 01:04:20.080
[Guest]: to be done to help the economy has to be done by the RBI. And the entire burden of controlling

01:04:20.080 --> 01:04:24.360
[Guest]: inflation, which is, you know, by that time, when Pranab Mukherjee was in office at one

01:04:24.360 --> 01:04:29.920
[Guest]: point, you know, inflation reaches 20%. And Pranab Mukherjee and his team of officials

01:04:29.920 --> 01:04:34.560
[Guest]: in North Block are not willing to do anything about it. And they just keep telling the RBI

01:04:34.560 --> 01:04:38.280
[Guest]: governor that, you know, whatever has to be done has to be done by you. It has to be done

01:04:38.280 --> 01:04:47.440
[Guest]: by the RBI. So, economic policy making coordination with RBI is not in a very good shape, you

01:04:47.440 --> 01:04:52.680
[Guest]: know, during Pranab Mukherjee's tenure. It's really, I mean, as finance minister, it's

01:04:52.680 --> 01:04:57.160
[Guest]: really difficult to look for what it is, you know, that goes right in the finance ministry

01:04:57.160 --> 01:04:58.160
[Guest]: in this period.

01:04:58.160 --> 01:05:04.280
[Amit Varma]: In fact, speaking of his, you know, clashes with the RBI, there's a great quote by him,

01:05:04.280 --> 01:05:08.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, an official who knew Mukherjee has quoted him as saying, which you reproduced

01:05:08.600 --> 01:05:12.760
[Amit Varma]: in your book, where Mukherjee says, quote, I can't do anything on the fiscal side because

01:05:12.760 --> 01:05:19.920
[Amit Varma]: of political compulsions. The RBI must therefore take full responsibility for reviving growth.

01:05:19.920 --> 01:05:25.080
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And for a moment, you know, let's take a sidetrack here. And one of the sort

01:05:25.080 --> 01:05:31.040
[Amit Varma]: of themes that runs through your book and the policymaking is, firstly, the role of

01:05:31.040 --> 01:05:37.320
[Amit Varma]: the RBI, its tenuous relationship with different governments, and also the fundamental issue

01:05:37.320 --> 01:05:42.720
[Amit Varma]: of inflation, where Mukherjee, of course, assumed that, you know, inflation could simply

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:47.680
[Amit Varma]: be managed by the RBI with monetary policy, which, of course, is not the case. And, you

01:05:47.680 --> 01:05:51.840
[Amit Varma]: know, there were constant tensions that often comes up is with lowering interest rates,

01:05:51.840 --> 01:05:57.000
[Amit Varma]: whereas you point out, politicians will always want the RBI to lower interest rates because

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:01.040
[Amit Varma]: their interest groups are happy, you have more money going into the economy, and all

01:06:01.040 --> 01:06:04.560
[Amit Varma]: the big corporate houses that funds them are getting cheaper money, and that's what they

01:06:04.560 --> 01:06:09.200
[Amit Varma]: want. So their imperatives are in that direction. But the more you lower interest rates, the

01:06:09.200 --> 01:06:13.960
[Amit Varma]: more you raise the chance of inflation, because you have more money chasing fewer goods. And

01:06:13.960 --> 01:06:18.440
[Amit Varma]: therefore, the RBI is always sort of pushing back against them. And this is a constant

01:06:18.440 --> 01:06:23.240
[Amit Varma]: tussle over the years. So, you know, through through this period, in fact, the entire 10

01:06:23.240 --> 01:06:27.240
[Amit Varma]: years for that matter, can you just kind of sum up what were the sort of stresses between

01:06:27.240 --> 01:06:29.560
[Amit Varma]: the RBI and the governments of the time?

01:06:29.560 --> 01:06:36.520
[Guest]: Yeah, so the stress between the RBI and the government can be seen throughout this 10

01:06:36.520 --> 01:06:42.440
[Guest]: year period, it is of one nature in the time of the UPA, because they're the main fight

01:06:42.440 --> 01:06:49.520
[Guest]: for the RBI is against inflation. And it becomes a little different in the post 2014 period,

01:06:49.520 --> 01:06:55.440
[Guest]: where the government's change, because they're the nature of the problem that the RBI is

01:06:55.440 --> 01:07:01.560
[Guest]: attacking changes, inflation comes under control. And if you see that it comes under control,

01:07:01.560 --> 01:07:09.080
[Guest]: because Urjit Patel and Raghuram Rajan starting 2013, take a very strict stance against inflation,

01:07:09.080 --> 01:07:13.200
[Guest]: and they get for minimum for a small window of 18 months, when Peter Dumpram comes back

01:07:13.200 --> 01:07:18.240
[Guest]: as the finance minister, they get support from him, because I guess, Peter Dumpram and

01:07:18.240 --> 01:07:23.280
[Guest]: you know, Manmohan Singh are in tune with the RBI a little more than the other political

01:07:23.280 --> 01:07:28.400
[Guest]: leaders who become finance ministers. And they, you know, they start to take steps and

01:07:28.400 --> 01:07:32.800
[Guest]: of course, Narendra Modi government's record on inflation is a lot better. And it has helped

01:07:32.800 --> 01:07:38.440
[Guest]: a great deal by international oil prices. So RBI is no longer fighting inflation, you

01:07:38.440 --> 01:07:46.760
[Guest]: know, post 2014, they need to support growth. Either way, the tussle between the RBI and

01:07:46.760 --> 01:07:52.840
[Guest]: the government comes, because for some reason, finance ministers and politicians in India

01:07:52.840 --> 01:07:58.280
[Guest]: have just assumed that the only way to reduce inflation is interest rate policy. The only

01:07:58.280 --> 01:08:02.920
[Guest]: way to support growth is interest rate policy. And fiscal policy can be whatever, you know,

01:08:02.920 --> 01:08:08.240
[Guest]: their political compulsions dictated to be. Either they have assumed this or that, you

01:08:08.240 --> 01:08:15.800
[Guest]: know, they pretend this is what they know. But, you know, in India, the interest rate

01:08:15.800 --> 01:08:24.400
[Guest]: policy cannot only be determined by the needs of the industrialists for capital, because

01:08:24.400 --> 01:08:29.840
[Guest]: Indians are savers. We have a huge section of our society that depends on its savings

01:08:29.840 --> 01:08:37.080
[Guest]: for, you know, retirement growth. And we, you know, they are a dispersed group. They

01:08:37.080 --> 01:08:43.040
[Guest]: are, they are not as vocal as corporate lobbies and industrial lobbies are. They would like

01:08:43.040 --> 01:08:46.680
[Guest]: interest rates to be high. Corporate lobbies would like interest rates to be low. Corporate

01:08:46.680 --> 01:08:53.840
[Guest]: lobbies are very organized in getting themselves heard by finance ministers. And, you know,

01:08:53.840 --> 01:09:00.520
[Guest]: the RBI, in the end, becomes the only institution that is sensitive to the needs of the savers

01:09:00.520 --> 01:09:08.960
[Guest]: in the economy. And also inflation, which is a tax on poor people. I quote Y. V. Reddy

01:09:08.960 --> 01:09:13.640
[Guest]: in the book, I quote from his book, where he says that, you know, the political consensus

01:09:13.640 --> 01:09:20.760
[Guest]: in India, you know, until about 2005, seemed to be that the level of inflation after which,

01:09:20.760 --> 01:09:27.040
[Guest]: you know, politicians begin to get sensitive until that was as high as 10%, you know, whereas,

01:09:27.040 --> 01:09:33.760
[Guest]: and he also explains that, you know, when inflation is high, what we don't realize is

01:09:33.760 --> 01:09:41.480
[Guest]: that the shock of that on poor people can set them back in ways where, you know, slowly,

01:09:41.480 --> 01:09:47.160
[Guest]: even if you bring inflation under control, they may not return, you know, back to that

01:09:47.160 --> 01:09:51.960
[Guest]: normal position from where they had started losing because the poor have very low ability

01:09:51.960 --> 01:09:59.520
[Guest]: to take, to absorb shocks to their incomes, which is not the case, you know, for people

01:09:59.520 --> 01:10:05.080
[Guest]: who are not poor. And therefore, the RBI must always be more sensitive, you know, to inflation

01:10:05.080 --> 01:10:11.400
[Guest]: type concerns. And it's very strange that politicians, according to him, do not display

01:10:11.400 --> 01:10:19.200
[Guest]: this sensitivity of the poor and their incomes to inflation shocks. Of course, in the UPA

01:10:19.200 --> 01:10:24.160
[Guest]: 2 tenure, there are some factors of inflation that are beyond their control, which is oil

01:10:24.160 --> 01:10:29.840
[Guest]: prices, but during the tenure of Pranab Mukherjee, a lot of that inflation is because of his

01:10:29.840 --> 01:10:39.600
[Guest]: fiscal policies. And he just refuses to listen to the RBI governor on that. And, in fact,

01:10:39.600 --> 01:10:43.560
[Guest]: the RBI governor D. Subba Rao, I quote from his book, and I also quote him in his conversations

01:10:43.560 --> 01:10:47.880
[Guest]: with me for this book, where he says that, you know, he goes and meets routinely, he

01:10:47.880 --> 01:10:52.640
[Guest]: meets the Prime Minister and the Prime Minister, you know, keeps bringing up this point. And

01:10:52.640 --> 01:10:57.040
[Guest]: he explains to the Prime Minister why inflation is high, why what needs to be done, you know,

01:10:57.040 --> 01:11:01.560
