01:13:37.280 --> 01:13:44.560
[Amit Varma]: So to go back to the political morality played as unfolding during Pranam Mukherjee's tenure,

01:13:44.560 --> 01:13:48.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you point out how number one, he's not carrying out any of the reforms that are

01:13:48.720 --> 01:13:53.760
[Amit Varma]: desperately required, especially the structural reforms that will, you know, boost manufacturing

01:13:53.760 --> 01:13:59.880
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. Secondly, you point out about his, you know, how fiscally he's gone haywire.

01:13:59.880 --> 01:14:04.640
[Amit Varma]: There's a lot more money being pumped into the economy and social sector spending goes

01:14:04.640 --> 01:14:11.040
[Amit Varma]: up enormously because of political imperatives. The third thing, which I'd like you to quickly

01:14:11.040 --> 01:14:16.200
[Amit Varma]: sort of mention that you talk about at length in your book is the policy paralysis that

01:14:16.200 --> 01:14:18.440
[Amit Varma]: comes about because of the 2G scam.

01:14:18.440 --> 01:14:24.880
[Guest]: Yes. So there, I think it's got a lot more to do with the role of the CAG, the role of

01:14:24.880 --> 01:14:29.920
[Guest]: the opposition and the role of the media. Also, you know, how things played out in courts,

01:14:29.920 --> 01:14:38.600
[Guest]: where this scam scares decision makers and government so much that they stop approving

01:14:38.600 --> 01:14:45.080
[Guest]: files and files stop moving. Now, remember, this comes at a point when, because there

01:14:45.080 --> 01:14:49.560
[Guest]: was a boom in the economy and Indian corporate sector and industrialists were hopeful that,

01:14:49.560 --> 01:14:53.960
[Guest]: you know, that trajectory will continue. It is because of betting on that trajectory,

01:14:53.960 --> 01:14:58.280
[Guest]: they have taken a lot of loans and started a lot of projects and they may have gone overboard

01:14:58.280 --> 01:15:02.240
[Guest]: as Raghuram Rajan says, there was an over exuberance. They've taken more loans than

01:15:02.240 --> 01:15:07.400
[Guest]: they ideally should have. And, but the global financial crisis, an unexpected event takes

01:15:07.400 --> 01:15:14.080
[Guest]: place. And those, you know, investment decisions need to be reassessed in light of, you know,

01:15:14.080 --> 01:15:19.160
[Guest]: the changed economic scenario, but because the economy is handled well, you know, the

01:15:19.160 --> 01:15:24.640
[Guest]: growth does not collapse. Instead of recalibrating their investment decisions and exuberance,

01:15:24.640 --> 01:15:29.080
[Guest]: what the corporate sector does is it extends itself even further. And then when because

01:15:29.080 --> 01:15:34.840
[Guest]: of Ranam Mukherjee's policies and other economic shocks, such as inflation, you know, the economy

01:15:34.840 --> 01:15:42.560
[Guest]: doesn't do as well. And this 2G scam happens, the projects get delayed or stuck. The investment

01:15:42.560 --> 01:15:48.280
[Guest]: calculations of companies go haywire instead of, you know, saying that I'm not going to

01:15:48.280 --> 01:15:52.800
[Guest]: do as much as I thought I'll recalibrate. What they do is they, they ask for more loans,

01:15:52.800 --> 01:15:57.360
[Guest]: you know, they further extend themselves and banks very willingly extend even more roles.

01:15:57.360 --> 01:16:00.960
[Guest]: And there again, I described how the seeds of this NPA crisis is actually sown at the

01:16:00.960 --> 01:16:05.520
[Guest]: time of when Ranam Mukherjee is in the finance ministry and there's a complete failure of

01:16:05.520 --> 01:16:12.360
[Guest]: oversight, you know, and so companies take further loans and no policies are being taken

01:16:12.360 --> 01:16:17.720
[Guest]: because of which the economy just doesn't recover and projects keep getting stuck. Bureaucrats

01:16:17.720 --> 01:16:22.720
[Guest]: don't take decisions. And there is a complete paralysis in the economy where approvals are

01:16:22.720 --> 01:16:26.960
[Guest]: not taking place, more and more loans are being taken so that projects don't die. And

01:16:26.960 --> 01:16:31.400
[Guest]: there's an incentive. I described how, you know, the banks are also, they think it is

01:16:31.400 --> 01:16:36.360
[Guest]: in their interest to ever green these loans instead of cut their losses and, you know,

01:16:36.360 --> 01:16:41.800
[Guest]: write off and say that, you know, this project is not viable anymore. Let me, you know, just

01:16:41.800 --> 01:16:47.480
[Guest]: sort of put that in my books. They also don't do that. So that's how there's a policy

01:16:47.480 --> 01:16:52.600
[Guest]: paralysis that gets converted into a big NPA crisis. And eventually that NPA crisis comes

01:16:52.600 --> 01:16:58.040
[Guest]: back in the tenure of Narendra Modi government, it becomes a complete banking paralysis where

01:16:58.040 --> 01:17:01.720
[Guest]: then there is, you know, credit flow in the economy completely gets choked and there's

01:17:01.720 --> 01:17:06.080
[Guest]: no money, banks have no money, you know, to extend credit because in between, you know,

01:17:06.080 --> 01:17:12.280
[Guest]: comes this new RBI governor who forces everybody to become, you know, more honest about what

01:17:12.280 --> 01:17:18.680
[Guest]: is the kind of NPA sitting on their bank books, they can't hide it anymore. And, you know,

01:17:18.680 --> 01:17:25.080
[Guest]: that's a huge part of the economy, where things are not going right in this decade.

01:17:25.080 --> 01:17:30.280
[Amit Varma]: And I have a sort of a broader philosophical question here, which is that, you know, the

01:17:30.280 --> 01:17:35.640
[Amit Varma]: policy paralysis as you've as you've laid out got exacerbated and, you know, led to

01:17:35.640 --> 01:17:41.400
[Amit Varma]: NPAs becoming worse because people were scared to take action and even outside of that domain

01:17:41.400 --> 01:17:46.160
[Amit Varma]: bureaucrats were afraid to do anything that could lead them later to be accused of corruption.

01:17:46.160 --> 01:17:52.480
[Amit Varma]: So my broad question here is that there is, you know, everyone would agree that government

01:17:52.480 --> 01:17:56.360
[Amit Varma]: needs to be transparent, and they need to be there needs to be scrutiny of all decisions

01:17:56.360 --> 01:18:01.440
[Amit Varma]: that are made. So there seems here to be some kind of trade off between scrutiny and paralysis

01:18:01.440 --> 01:18:05.840
[Amit Varma]: that on the other hand, you need a certain amount of scrutiny to keep government honest.

01:18:05.840 --> 01:18:11.200
[Amit Varma]: But on the flip side of that, as we saw in this case is that if officials become terrified

01:18:11.200 --> 01:18:16.600
[Amit Varma]: of doing anything at all, you know, like in the 2g case, for example, like you've eloquently

01:18:16.600 --> 01:18:21.680
[Amit Varma]: described in your book, and I'll ask my listeners to check that out, is that what the government

01:18:21.680 --> 01:18:26.920
[Amit Varma]: claimed was that they were, you know, looking at a trade off between revenue optimization

01:18:26.920 --> 01:18:32.360
[Amit Varma]: and welfare optimization, and they went on the side of welfare and therefore, but then

01:18:32.360 --> 01:18:37.800
[Amit Varma]: later that was thrown back in their face, as if the revenue foregone was a was an example

01:18:37.800 --> 01:18:43.040
[Amit Varma]: of corruption and leaving aside the merits of that particular case, how does one resolve

01:18:43.040 --> 01:18:47.600
[Amit Varma]: this trade off in this conflict between scrutiny and paralysis?

01:18:47.600 --> 01:18:54.440
[Guest]: I think this is a leadership failure, political leadership, I discussed this point with Peter

01:18:54.440 --> 01:18:59.040
[Guest]: Dumbrin in the book, and he agrees and I mean, you know, so so what I'm trying to say is

01:18:59.040 --> 01:19:03.760
[Guest]: that there is probably this is how even the government of the day felt that this is completely

01:19:03.760 --> 01:19:09.600
[Guest]: a political leadership, you see, why did the 2g scam become such a thing of scare the the

01:19:09.600 --> 01:19:17.160
[Guest]: overzealous investigative agencies, why did they become such a scare for all bureaucrats

01:19:17.160 --> 01:19:21.840
[Guest]: across the board, because let's not forget, the first instinct of a bureaucrat is self

01:19:21.840 --> 01:19:28.920
[Guest]: preservation, what they were seeing is that what should have been a policy decision had

01:19:28.920 --> 01:19:34.800
[Guest]: been presented as a scam. And cam theory had got so much purchase in the media and in the

01:19:34.800 --> 01:19:40.720
[Guest]: political setup that you know, the courts found it difficult to not not take it up.

01:19:40.720 --> 01:19:47.240
[Guest]: And the whole thing became such a huge controversy. I don't think you know, any bureaucrat would

01:19:47.240 --> 01:19:52.240
[Guest]: have reacted in any different way. I mean, why should I take a decision and tomorrow

01:19:52.240 --> 01:19:58.320
[Guest]: be questioned about it, rather than not take a decision and you know, retire safely. So

01:19:58.320 --> 01:20:03.480
[Guest]: I think bureaucrats were acting very, very rationally. And what was happening is that

01:20:03.480 --> 01:20:10.120
[Guest]: the whole thing really got very politicized, very controversial. And this trade off how

01:20:10.120 --> 01:20:15.680
[Guest]: to prevent this, I think, you know, there has to be a balance of information. Why did

01:20:15.680 --> 01:20:21.200
[Guest]: this happen? There was asymmetry of information, the media was playing it up, the you know,

01:20:21.200 --> 01:20:25.000
[Guest]: opposition in parliament was playing it up, the government was keeping quiet. And there's

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:29.280
[Guest]: a long description from an interview that Salman Khurshid has given, you know, to the

01:20:29.280 --> 01:20:34.560
[Guest]: Hindu newspaper, where he describes how there was absolute lack of clarity within the government

01:20:34.560 --> 01:20:38.920
[Guest]: on how to handle this political. This was a political crisis. This was not an administration

01:20:38.920 --> 01:20:44.000
[Guest]: crisis. It was not an economic crisis. This particular case, it was a completely political

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:52.480
[Guest]: crisis. And because of the duality of authority in the UPA between Sonia Gandhi and Manmohan

01:20:52.480 --> 01:20:57.000
[Guest]: Singh, the cabinet just didn't know how to handle this. And Salman Khurshid says, this

01:20:57.000 --> 01:21:01.440
[Guest]: is the first time, you know, in the Congress that this has happened always, their political

01:21:01.440 --> 01:21:05.520
[Guest]: party leadership and Prime Minister were always one individual. So they didn't know how to

01:21:05.520 --> 01:21:10.520
[Guest]: go about this. They were not able to counter, you know, things that were being said, and

01:21:10.520 --> 01:21:12.520
[Amit Varma]: it just got out of hand.

01:21:12.520 --> 01:21:17.280
[Amit Varma]: And you know, as always happens when I am three quarters of the way through an episode

01:21:17.280 --> 01:21:21.360
[Amit Varma]: as often happens is that I realized that a book is so good that I can't possibly do justice

01:21:21.360 --> 01:21:25.800
[Amit Varma]: to all of it during the episode. So out of your four chapters, I'm going to quickly summarize

01:21:25.800 --> 01:21:30.440
[Amit Varma]: what your third chapter is about. And I encourage listeners to read that for themselves, because

01:21:30.440 --> 01:21:34.720
[Amit Varma]: I'd rather go to the fourth very fascinating chapter of the Modi years. But the third chapter

01:21:34.720 --> 01:21:44.240
[Amit Varma]: basically is about how just as serendipity took us backwards by giving us Pranam Mukherjee

01:21:44.240 --> 01:21:49.680
[Amit Varma]: as a finance minister, it also then helped us out where, you know, one of his possible

01:21:49.680 --> 01:21:53.640
[Amit Varma]: lifelong ambitions of becoming president since the prime ministership seemed out of reach

01:21:53.640 --> 01:21:58.440
[Amit Varma]: was finally fulfilled. And because he could become president, Chidambaram could, you know,

01:21:58.440 --> 01:22:03.000
[Amit Varma]: with 18 months left to go for the elections, become finance minister again, and start taking

01:22:03.000 --> 01:22:07.240
[Amit Varma]: some really hard decisions for the economy. And I'll just quote his own words from it,

01:22:07.240 --> 01:22:13.200
[Amit Varma]: as you've quoted in your book about what happened. Quote, fiscal deficit was sharply reduced.

01:22:13.200 --> 01:22:17.560
[Amit Varma]: The current account deficit, in fact, had been contained substantially by squeezing.

01:22:17.560 --> 01:22:23.040
[Amit Varma]: Some very harsh decisions were taken, which of course affected growth. And it did not

01:22:23.040 --> 01:22:28.560
[Amit Varma]: give us the kind of advantage that we should have got if inflation had been lower. Ultimately,

01:22:28.560 --> 01:22:34.080
[Amit Varma]: we lost the 2014 Lok Sabha elections partly on apart from the corruption charges, we lost

01:22:34.080 --> 01:22:39.360
[Amit Varma]: our inflation, stop quote. And this is again very interesting where you have an economist

01:22:39.360 --> 01:22:44.220
[Amit Varma]: who really gets it. And he gets that this is almost like a crisis brewing and something

01:22:44.220 --> 01:22:50.480
[Amit Varma]: needs to be done. And he takes decisions, which essentially harms him and his party

01:22:50.480 --> 01:22:51.480
[Amit Varma]: politically.

01:22:51.480 --> 01:22:58.560
[Guest]: Yes, I do see that, you know, in what he says that, you know, these are these trade offs

01:22:58.560 --> 01:23:04.760
[Guest]: that have to be made. And, you know, he makes those trade offs as the person in charge.

01:23:04.760 --> 01:23:09.640
[Guest]: I do argue in this third chapter that, you know, the sort of political landscape was

01:23:09.640 --> 01:23:16.200
[Guest]: made fertile because of this high inflation and, you know, really mismanagement of the

01:23:16.200 --> 01:23:20.040
[Guest]: economy by the UPA government. And there are various other things discussed, like, you

01:23:20.040 --> 01:23:24.400
[Guest]: know, why the food inflation was so high and Sharad Pawar's role comes in there. And because

01:23:24.400 --> 01:23:29.720
[Guest]: of the corruption charges, it is because of this economic discontent. This is my theory.

01:23:29.720 --> 01:23:34.880
[Guest]: And it is for political analysts and experts to examine if I may be right or wrong. This

01:23:34.880 --> 01:23:40.720
[Guest]: is what I sort of speculate, you know, whether because the economic discontent made the political

01:23:40.720 --> 01:23:46.000
[Guest]: landscape fertile, there are a lot of promises that were made by Narendra Modi in his campaign

01:23:46.000 --> 01:23:52.440
[Guest]: starting September 2013, that sort of got the kind of purchase from voters that it did.

01:23:52.440 --> 01:23:56.400
[Guest]: So the land for that was made, political landscape for that was made fertile by the economic

01:23:56.400 --> 01:24:03.040
[Guest]: mismanagement by the UPA too, ironically headed by a distinguished economist. And the start

01:24:03.040 --> 01:24:08.000
[Guest]: of the Modi wave is actually because of the complete economic mismanagement by the UPA

01:24:08.000 --> 01:24:09.000
[Amit Varma]: too.

01:24:09.000 --> 01:24:14.640
[Amit Varma]: Right. So, you know, so Modi comes to power in 2014. Tell me a little bit about what is

01:24:14.640 --> 01:24:19.760
[Amit Varma]: Modi's approach to governance and economics, because it seems to start off well where he

01:24:19.760 --> 01:24:24.880
[Amit Varma]: makes as he did during campaigning, he makes all the right noises. He has no shortage of

01:24:24.880 --> 01:24:31.240
[Amit Varma]: good advisors. You know, Ela Patnaik is part of the setup and, you know, the Niti Aayog

01:24:31.240 --> 01:24:35.600
[Amit Varma]: is set up with Panagaria and so on. But what is Modi's own approach to economics and the

01:24:35.600 --> 01:24:37.760
[Guest]: problems that India faces then?

01:24:37.760 --> 01:24:47.040
[Guest]: Oh, actually, good question. In the last chapter, you know, I asked this exact same question

01:24:47.040 --> 01:24:53.100
[Guest]: of Mr. Arun Jaitley. And I quote his answers to me, you know, on Mr. Modi's whole approach

01:24:53.100 --> 01:25:00.900
[Guest]: to economic policy. And what those answers tell me is that Mr. Modi is more politically

01:25:00.900 --> 01:25:09.640
[Guest]: inclined. And, you know, whatever he does, whatever decisions he takes, it is on the

01:25:09.640 --> 01:25:16.480
[Guest]: basis of the political gains that can be expected from those. And I think a lot of it depends

01:25:16.480 --> 01:25:22.400
[Guest]: on who it is who's briefing him about what needs to be done and what the problem is.

01:25:22.400 --> 01:25:28.280
[Guest]: So when he starts in 2014, I described this whole, you know, meeting that he does with

01:25:28.280 --> 01:25:33.680
[Guest]: all the secretaries to government and how he makes all the right noises. All the bureaucrats

01:25:33.680 --> 01:25:38.840
[Guest]: in Lutyens Delhi, you know, 80 secretaries to government defender, how excited and thrilled

01:25:38.840 --> 01:25:43.760
[Guest]: they are that the phase of policy paralysis has ended. And finally, they're going to be,

01:25:43.760 --> 01:25:50.520
[Guest]: you know, headed by a decisive Prime Minister and they're going to be taking decisions.

01:25:50.520 --> 01:25:57.400
[Guest]: But as the months progress, it becomes clear that, you know, not only is Mr. Modi complete

01:25:57.400 --> 01:26:04.880
[Guest]: polar opposite of Dr. Manmohan Singh, he's also, he's very close to the ground. And what

01:26:04.880 --> 01:26:12.720
[Guest]: appeals to him is, you know, programs and schemes, Swachh Bharat, you know, there's

01:26:12.720 --> 01:26:18.840
[Guest]: a whole long list of programs that bureaucrats design and he loves to go and inaugurate them.

01:26:18.840 --> 01:26:26.120
[Guest]: And he has these solutions for things that he has seen as a chief minister go wrong.

01:26:26.120 --> 01:26:32.320
[Guest]: But you know, I quote bureaucrats there where they begin to wonder very soon, is that really

01:26:32.320 --> 01:26:38.760
[Guest]: the job at the center of a prime minister? We have some reason to believe that Mr. Modi

01:26:38.760 --> 01:26:44.480
[Guest]: has a more chief minister like approach to his prime ministership, which has its plus

01:26:44.480 --> 01:26:52.000
[Guest]: points and its negative points. Plus points because he's less ivory tower type, you know,

01:26:52.000 --> 01:26:58.160
[Guest]: than prime ministers can be. But negative points because really the job of the center's

01:26:58.160 --> 01:27:06.960
[Guest]: policymaking, you know, correcting for policy errors, and programs and schemes cannot substitute

01:27:06.960 --> 01:27:15.720
[Guest]: for policymaking. And so, Mr. Modi's heard that economic reforms need to be done. He's

01:27:15.720 --> 01:27:22.280
[Guest]: built a campaign on the jobs crisis in 2014, he promises jobs. And he's obviously been

01:27:22.280 --> 01:27:29.480
[Guest]: briefed by his economic advisors that land reforms, labor reforms, GST, make in India

01:27:29.480 --> 01:27:35.680
[Guest]: the way to go forward and fix all the problems of the economy. And, you know, he's doing

01:27:35.680 --> 01:27:42.240
[Guest]: that. He does that in 2014 and 15. But the minute he faces his first political crisis,

01:27:42.240 --> 01:27:50.760
[Guest]: he loses faith in all of that. In 2014, not only did he win the 2014 Lok Sabha election,

01:27:50.760 --> 01:27:57.280
[Guest]: there are a lot of state elections, assembly elections that the BJP wins quite handsomely.

01:27:57.280 --> 01:28:06.560
[Guest]: But starting 2015, in February, they get a root shock in Delhi. And through 2015, that's

01:28:06.560 --> 01:28:11.640
[Guest]: really a turning point for the Modi government, the year 2015. Through 2015, they face a lot

01:28:11.640 --> 01:28:18.360
[Guest]: of political crisis in Parliament, when the Congress raises the slogan of Sood Boot Ki

01:28:18.360 --> 01:28:24.280
[Guest]: Sarkar, and they oppose the land reforms. And you know, the land amendment legislation

01:28:24.280 --> 01:28:28.640
[Guest]: that the Modi government has brought in Parliament, and they have promulgated an ordinance and

01:28:28.640 --> 01:28:34.760
[Guest]: it has been re-promulgated multiple times, they finally are forced to allow it to lapse.

01:28:34.760 --> 01:28:39.000
[Guest]: Because by November, there are no other state assembly elections through 2015. But in November,

01:28:39.000 --> 01:28:45.400
[Guest]: there is the Bihar election where again, they had a root shock. And I think in 2015, internally,

01:28:45.400 --> 01:28:52.120
[Guest]: they really begin to ask themselves, has the Modi wave ended? Has it ended? And like I

01:28:52.120 --> 01:29:00.640
[Guest]: said, it happened at the time of the Vajpayee government losing election. The way the politician

01:29:00.640 --> 01:29:05.320
[Guest]: thinks that reforms do not get me elected. And therefore, let me now do something that

01:29:05.320 --> 01:29:10.240
[Guest]: will get me elected. And therefore, what the BJP decides to do is they need to reinvent

01:29:10.240 --> 01:29:16.240
[Guest]: Mr. Modi's image as somebody who's pro-poor. They need a scheme which they think will match

01:29:16.240 --> 01:29:21.800
[Guest]: up to what the NREGA was for which they believe that, you know, UPA2 was voted back to power

01:29:21.800 --> 01:29:27.760
[Guest]: because of NREGA. And they have to, the other thing is that, you know, a big part of their

01:29:27.760 --> 01:29:34.560
[Guest]: campaign was the black money issue, the corruption issue, where Arvind Kejriwal's win in Delhi

01:29:34.560 --> 01:29:39.160
[Guest]: shows them that, you know, he may now just walk away with the mantle of, you know, corruption

01:29:39.160 --> 01:29:43.400
[Guest]: and black money and they need to do something. They've taken many steps. There have been

01:29:43.400 --> 01:29:48.120
[Guest]: lots of things that they have done for black money, but nothing is, you know, everything

01:29:48.120 --> 01:29:51.600
[Guest]: has produced very moderate results. There's nothing they can go to the voters with and

01:29:51.600 --> 01:29:55.280
[Guest]: say, see, this is what we've done against corruption and black money. And therefore,

01:29:55.280 --> 01:30:02.600
[Guest]: you know, there is a kind of a rethinking that takes place in 2015 in the BJP. And it

01:30:02.600 --> 01:30:09.080
[Guest]: takes them back to the drawing board and they come up with demonetization as the solution.

01:30:09.080 --> 01:30:14.160
[Guest]: And not only do they come up with demonetization, they bury all plans for land reforms, for

01:30:14.160 --> 01:30:20.920
[Guest]: labor reforms. Make in India takes a side seat. The Prime Minister stops talking about

01:30:20.920 --> 01:30:25.840
[Guest]: Make in India at his public events. He talks now all the time about farmers, doubling farmer

01:30:25.840 --> 01:30:32.680
[Guest]: incomes and things like that. So he kind of reorients, he reinvents his image, but he

01:30:32.680 --> 01:30:38.760
[Guest]: also very successfully and he, you know, reorients his government policy away from reforms and

01:30:38.760 --> 01:30:46.680
[Guest]: towards, you know, what he thinks will have purchase with voters. And yeah, so that's

01:30:46.680 --> 01:30:53.440
[Guest]: the story really of how, you know, Mr. Modi sort of responds to economic policy.

01:30:53.440 --> 01:30:57.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, I've had a number of episodes on demonetization, I'll link them from the episode

01:30:57.600 --> 01:31:01.600
[Amit Varma]: page which cover all the economic aspects of it. But what I particularly found fascinating

01:31:01.600 --> 01:31:08.120
[Amit Varma]: in your book was the political narrative behind it, which, again, underscores how to Modi

01:31:08.120 --> 01:31:13.440
[Amit Varma]: governance doesn't matter at all, only optics does. So it's not that he wants to solve the

01:31:13.440 --> 01:31:17.400
[Amit Varma]: problem of black money or even understand why that problem exists. He just wants to

01:31:17.400 --> 01:31:21.920
[Amit Varma]: be seen to be solving it. It's not that he actually wants to be pro poor. In fact, he

01:31:21.920 --> 01:31:26.840
[Amit Varma]: just wants to be seen as pro poor. And, you know, at the root of all of this is, can I

01:31:26.840 --> 01:31:32.200
[Amit Varma]: get a rhetorical advantage from these things, and not a concern of whether those policies

01:31:32.200 --> 01:31:37.720
[Amit Varma]: will do harm or do good. And demon, of course, which, you know, I call the largest assault

01:31:37.720 --> 01:31:43.000
[Amit Varma]: on property rights in human history, was incredibly harmful for our economy. And we hardly need

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:48.760
[Amit Varma]: to elaborate on that. But even sort of apart from that, the very next year, they do GST,

01:31:48.760 --> 01:31:54.040
[Amit Varma]: which is a great idea, but which again, they managed to botch up in the way they they do

01:31:54.040 --> 01:31:55.520
[Guest]: it. Tell me a little bit about that.

01:31:55.520 --> 01:32:01.960
[Guest]: Yes. So as you're saying, I don't put it so starkly. But you know, Mr. Modi does not display

01:32:01.960 --> 01:32:10.320
[Guest]: an ability to go to the roots of a problem. He does not seem to ask the questions why

01:32:10.320 --> 01:32:15.800
[Guest]: something is happening. Why is there black money in the economy? He's very happy to,

01:32:15.800 --> 01:32:22.400
[Guest]: you know, come up with a scheme, which seems very grand. And it's the same approach, you

01:32:22.400 --> 01:32:28.720
[Guest]: know, for various economic policy decisions, but especially also for GST, where the very

01:32:28.720 --> 01:32:32.480
[Guest]: fact that his government has come up with the GST, and you know, he wants to launch

01:32:32.480 --> 01:32:38.880
[Guest]: it in the midnight session of Parliament, joint session of Parliament, his whole focus

01:32:38.880 --> 01:32:47.840
[Guest]: is on that. And his because of political complications, the GST Council has come up with, you know,

01:32:47.840 --> 01:32:54.920
[Guest]: multiple rate GST, which is very difficult to collect. And, you know, it is highly complicated.

01:32:54.920 --> 01:32:59.240
[Guest]: The collection of the GST is highly more than the rate structure, I described in the book

01:32:59.240 --> 01:33:04.640
[Guest]: how it is the compliances and the, you know, the collection mechanism, which is really

01:33:04.640 --> 01:33:12.480
[Guest]: complicated. He has not concerned himself as much with those aspects of GST. Further,

01:33:12.480 --> 01:33:19.440
[Guest]: you know, GST becomes, you know, a tool for political messaging. Before Gujarat elections,

01:33:19.440 --> 01:33:24.080
[Guest]: there are certain items, you know, which are closer to the hearts of Gujaratis, the GST

01:33:24.080 --> 01:33:32.400
[Guest]: rate on that is reduced. Now, a tax system which is sold as a reform to become a means

01:33:32.400 --> 01:33:39.520
[Guest]: of political messaging, tells you a lot, you know, about the whole approach of the Modi

01:33:39.520 --> 01:33:47.680
[Guest]: government to reforms in GST. I mean, I can't see why, you know, Mr. Modi did not approach

01:33:47.680 --> 01:33:57.880
[Guest]: the whole GST designing issue more, in a more fundamental way. How is it that GST became

01:33:57.880 --> 01:34:04.040
[Guest]: what it has today? I cannot imagine it is because the pressure was from the state governments

01:34:04.040 --> 01:34:10.120
[Guest]: in the GST council for the GST to be like this, because the example of the Gujarati

01:34:10.120 --> 01:34:16.880
[Guest]: savories, the rates on it, that has come from the BJP ruled state, you know, it is obviously

01:34:16.880 --> 01:34:22.520
[Guest]: influenced by the BJP's politics and not by the other state governments. So clearly, you

01:34:22.520 --> 01:34:32.280
[Guest]: know, a tax reform becomes a tool for political messaging and gets botched up in the process.

01:34:32.280 --> 01:34:38.320
[Guest]: And there's no thought given to what it will do in the economy, what it will do for taxpayers

01:34:38.320 --> 01:34:43.920
[Guest]: and how it will make life very difficult for those, you know, people who now suddenly overnight

01:34:43.920 --> 01:34:49.320
[Guest]: become exposed to the tax jurisdictions. If you're doing business in, you know, all the

01:34:49.320 --> 01:34:55.800
[Guest]: 20 plus states, you're going to now have to be exposed to the tax jurisdictions of tax

01:34:55.800 --> 01:35:00.360
[Guest]: authorities of 28 states, not just the center and that one state where you operate, you

01:35:00.360 --> 01:35:03.120
[Guest]: know, so that obviously has not been thought through.

01:35:03.120 --> 01:35:08.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I've had a few episodes in GST as well, which again, I'll link these are like pet

01:35:08.160 --> 01:35:14.280
[Amit Varma]: subjects demon in GST. You know, one of the sort of things that struck me about the book

01:35:14.280 --> 01:35:20.680
[Amit Varma]: is that the two men who were prime minister through this period, are both extremes in

01:35:20.680 --> 01:35:26.780
[Amit Varma]: a bad way. For example, I couldn't help but contrast the fact that Manmohan simply did

01:35:26.780 --> 01:35:31.320
[Amit Varma]: not assert himself enough, the PMO was very weak during his time, and he allowed Pranab

01:35:31.320 --> 01:35:36.440
[Amit Varma]: to do all these things, even when he knew that, you know, they would harm the nation.

01:35:36.440 --> 01:35:42.280
[Amit Varma]: And on the opposite side, you see Modi who goes to the other extreme, and he doesn't

01:35:42.280 --> 01:35:47.160
[Amit Varma]: consult any experts or you know, even though they're available to him, he doesn't take

01:35:47.160 --> 01:35:51.480
[Amit Varma]: considered decisions, he is just too decisive, he just goes ahead and does whatever the hell

01:35:51.480 --> 01:35:56.440
[Amit Varma]: he wants. And some of it is absolutely disastrous for us. So it's a contrast between a PM who

01:35:56.440 --> 01:36:02.160
[Amit Varma]: is perhaps too weak, and a PM against who is perhaps asserting himself too much. And

01:36:02.160 --> 01:36:08.080
[Amit Varma]: equally, it's a contrast between what seems to be a policy paralysis, not just of, you

01:36:08.080 --> 01:36:13.320
[Amit Varma]: know, in the in the senses typically used of officials and so on during UPA2, but also

01:36:13.320 --> 01:36:19.880
[Amit Varma]: in terms of the indecisiveness of Manmohan himself, versus the speedy and bad decision

01:36:19.880 --> 01:36:25.240
[Amit Varma]: making of Modi. And it's an interesting contrast. And just thinking aloud as I asked this question,

01:36:25.240 --> 01:36:31.320
[Amit Varma]: it strikes me that isn't politics more likely to come up with the second kind of leader

01:36:31.320 --> 01:36:36.160
[Amit Varma]: like Modi because he has more of these qualities which make for a good politician leave governance

01:36:36.160 --> 01:36:42.400
[Amit Varma]: aside. And Manmohan, after all, was sort of an accidental politician in a sense, and therefore

01:36:42.400 --> 01:36:45.360
[Amit Varma]: we are more likely to get Modi's than Manmohan's.

01:36:45.360 --> 01:36:52.520
[Guest]: I absolutely agree that, you know, speedy decisions, supporters of Mr. Modi, you know,

01:36:52.520 --> 01:36:57.480
[Guest]: one of the things that they say is that he's very decisive, and he takes quick decisions.

01:36:57.480 --> 01:37:03.160
[Guest]: And supposedly a great thing about the current government, the Modi government is that, you

01:37:03.160 --> 01:37:06.880
[Guest]: know, they take decisions, I mean, with a surprise, there's an element of surprise,

01:37:06.880 --> 01:37:11.640
[Guest]: we find out about it, then they announce it. I'm not sure those are good qualities. And

01:37:11.640 --> 01:37:16.200
[Guest]: I don't know why they're celebrated. You know, all this discourse that happens on whether

01:37:16.200 --> 01:37:21.080
[Guest]: something is a policy is good or bad, ideally should be preceded, you know, by the announcement.

01:37:21.080 --> 01:37:24.400
[Guest]: I mean, it should happen before the government makes up its mind, the government does not

01:37:24.400 --> 01:37:30.460
[Guest]: take on board all these analysis for the simple reason that it does not share its decision

01:37:30.460 --> 01:37:35.160
[Guest]: making, you know, well in advance, it only announces decisions. And I mean, speedy decisions

01:37:35.160 --> 01:37:41.880
[Guest]: are not necessarily good quality decisions, you know, so that certainly is a thing. And

01:37:41.880 --> 01:37:47.880
[Guest]: I also agree that Mr. Modi and Dr. Manmohan Singh are a study in contrasts. And, you know,

01:37:47.880 --> 01:37:56.800
[Guest]: a political system is more likely to come up with leaders who are perceived as strong

01:37:56.800 --> 01:38:07.920
[Guest]: rather than wise and sensitive. But in the current case, Amit, I would say that it is

01:38:07.920 --> 01:38:13.800
[Guest]: also likely that, you know, if you notice, at least I feel so that Mr. Modi has at all

01:38:13.800 --> 01:38:20.080
[Guest]: points pitched himself as absolute opposite to Dr. Manmohan Singh. It is because Dr. Manmohan

01:38:20.080 --> 01:38:26.200
[Guest]: Singh was called the weakest Prime Minister ever by Ms. Sushma Swaraj and Mr. Arun Jaitley

01:38:26.200 --> 01:38:30.720
[Guest]: in Parliament, which I also quote in the book, because he was the weakest, therefore, Mr.

01:38:30.720 --> 01:38:36.400
[Guest]: Modi is presented as the strongest, you know, so the plan or the, you know, the way they

01:38:36.400 --> 01:38:40.480
[Guest]: have strategized, perhaps, I don't know, I'm not, you know, I don't know what goes on in

01:38:40.480 --> 01:38:44.880
[Guest]: the BJP. I'm not a political reporter. But looking at it from the outside, it is one,

01:38:44.880 --> 01:38:50.120
[Guest]: you know, it is possible that the strategy is that, you know, Dr. Manmohan Singh is the

01:38:50.120 --> 01:38:54.720
[Guest]: weakest. So we have the solution to that we have the strongest, you know, that could also

01:38:54.720 --> 01:38:59.160
[Amit Varma]: be a possibility. Yeah, I think you sell yourself short by saying you're not a political reporter.

01:38:59.160 --> 01:39:03.520
[Amit Varma]: I think your book is packed with political insight. And, you know, I'm going to have

01:39:03.520 --> 01:39:07.440
[Amit Varma]: to end with one last question. But before I ask that question, I feel like I haven't

01:39:07.440 --> 01:39:11.440
[Amit Varma]: done justice to this book at all. So the next time you write a book, kindly give me six

01:39:11.440 --> 01:39:20.320
[Amit Varma]: hours of your time and come to the studio. And yeah, so here's the last sort of question

01:39:20.320 --> 01:39:26.880
[Amit Varma]: coming up for you, which is that, if you look forward to just the next five years of India's

01:39:26.880 --> 01:39:31.480
[Amit Varma]: economy, you know, leave aside of who wins the selections and so on, just if you look

01:39:31.480 --> 01:39:35.760
[Amit Varma]: forward to the next five years of India's economy, what's the best case scenario and

01:39:35.760 --> 01:39:39.680
[Guest]: what's the worst case scenario?

01:39:39.680 --> 01:39:46.920
[Guest]: So looking at the next five years, if I look at it as a continuation of the last 10 years,

01:39:46.920 --> 01:39:53.280
[Guest]: you know, unlike a lot of people, I do not see the last 10 years as Mr. Modi versus Dr.

01:39:53.280 --> 01:39:59.400
[Guest]: Singh. And I don't see too many differences between the UPA2 and the Modi government.

01:39:59.400 --> 01:40:06.360
[Guest]: What I see is that there is a certain slide and a certain failures and weakening of institutions

01:40:06.360 --> 01:40:13.760
[Guest]: that starts in UPA2, perhaps even before that, but I begin to document it in UPA2. And that

01:40:13.760 --> 01:40:21.040
[Guest]: slide deepens, you know, and takes proportions that in recent, you know, memory, we have

01:40:21.040 --> 01:40:27.440
[Guest]: not seen that happens in Mr. Modi's time. Now, if this slide continues, if it is not

01:40:27.440 --> 01:40:34.280
[Guest]: addressed, the worst case scenario is that we are already seeing the economy is slowing

01:40:34.280 --> 01:40:41.040
[Guest]: down once again. This time round, in the earlier phases, you know, whenever the economy was

01:40:41.040 --> 01:40:48.520
[Guest]: slowing down in the last 10 years, a fiscal stimulus or a correction in global oil prices,

01:40:48.520 --> 01:40:57.720
[Guest]: or some little bit economic policy decisions, generating positivity, succeeded in, you know,

01:40:57.720 --> 01:41:04.280
[Guest]: a small pickup in the economic growth rate, that may not have that kind of impact now.

01:41:04.280 --> 01:41:11.720
[Guest]: So what I'm trying to say is that stopping this slowdown and reversing it will not be

01:41:11.720 --> 01:41:17.120
[Guest]: as easy as it is, it has been in the last 10 years, you cannot just do a fiscal stimulus

01:41:17.120 --> 01:41:22.480
[Guest]: or a monetary stimulus and genuinely, you know, turn the trajectory, you're going to

01:41:22.480 --> 01:41:29.320
[Guest]: have to take some very tough decisions. Because we have wasted 10 years, you know, the need

01:41:29.320 --> 01:41:34.880
[Guest]: to take those difficult decisions has increased even more. And I quote in the book, the IMF

01:41:34.880 --> 01:41:40.600
[Guest]: article for both at the time of just before the 2014 elections and after that, where it

01:41:40.600 --> 01:41:46.040
[Guest]: clearly says that India is well past the stage where simple monetary and fiscal policy stimulus

01:41:46.040 --> 01:41:51.160
[Guest]: is going to, you know, be able to sustain growth momentum, it needs to do the hard reforms.

01:41:51.160 --> 01:41:55.880
[Guest]: And the main hard reform that they say is building human capital, which is the most

01:41:55.880 --> 01:42:00.720
[Guest]: difficult thing to do, you have to fix your education policy, you have to do something

01:42:00.720 --> 01:42:06.240
[Guest]: about public health. And it's only then, you know, that the true entrepreneurial capacity

01:42:06.240 --> 01:42:10.720
[Guest]: of Indians and potential of Indians will be unleashed. And that will translate into a

01:42:10.720 --> 01:42:16.160
[Guest]: collective economic growth, the demographic dividends that was being celebrated before

01:42:16.160 --> 01:42:20.720
[Guest]: the global financial crisis on the basis of which, you know, all the investments had been

01:42:20.720 --> 01:42:26.640
[Guest]: made in India, that demographic dividend could turn into a nightmare, you know, if the difficult

01:42:26.640 --> 01:42:34.680
[Guest]: decisions on reforms are not taken, and these youngsters cannot be, you know, gainfully

01:42:34.680 --> 01:42:42.640
[Guest]: employed in economic activity. The other thing is that, you know, the last 10 years, most

01:42:42.640 --> 01:42:50.800
[Guest]: of what has gone wrong is policy induced and mainly self inflicted wounds. There is very

01:42:50.800 --> 01:42:54.920
[Guest]: little, you know, which is because of external shocks, the taper tantrum, there's a small

01:42:54.920 --> 01:43:00.720
[Guest]: episode, which is a macroeconomic shock, the oil prices, small episode, that's an external

01:43:00.720 --> 01:43:04.200
[Guest]: shock. But other than that, everything that's going wrong is because of wrong policies that

01:43:04.200 --> 01:43:10.960
[Guest]: are being taken decisions that are being taken. And I see no signs of realization of how these

01:43:10.960 --> 01:43:16.760
[Guest]: decisions are poor quality decisions. And you look at, if you look at, you know, the

01:43:16.760 --> 01:43:25.000
[Guest]: farm prices, there's a long subsection of the farm prices in the book. You know, first,

01:43:25.000 --> 01:43:32.120
[Guest]: the Modi government experiments with MSP plus, you know, what they've promised, then they

01:43:32.120 --> 01:43:38.920
[Guest]: come up with the 6000 rupees, you know, PM Kisan scheme. In response to that, the Congress

01:43:38.920 --> 01:43:45.360
[Guest]: has come up with their Nehai scheme. And I call this the rise of populism. And in fact,

01:43:45.360 --> 01:43:50.520
[Guest]: the triumph of populism. But none of this is the real solution that the agriculture

01:43:50.520 --> 01:43:56.320
[Guest]: sector needs. And there is obviously no realization of that. There is no realization of why there

01:43:56.320 --> 01:44:04.320
[Guest]: is a job crisis. Make in India has taken, you know, has slipped off the priority list.

01:44:04.320 --> 01:44:11.320
[Guest]: So if we continue on this trajectory, the five things that I see is that almost immediately,

01:44:11.320 --> 01:44:14.760
[Guest]: you know, your growth momentum will slow down. We've already seen signs of that when we see

01:44:14.760 --> 01:44:22.880
[Guest]: production cuts announced by Maruti, etc. Two wheelers and all demand is the early indicators.

01:44:22.880 --> 01:44:28.080
[Guest]: And so, you know, a growth momentum slowdown, which means that your job crisis is not get

01:44:28.080 --> 01:44:33.000
[Guest]: taken care of, which means you're going to have this huge army of youngsters who are

01:44:33.000 --> 01:44:39.360
[Guest]: not gainfully employed in the economy, full of energy and perhaps soon frustration and

01:44:39.360 --> 01:44:45.800
[Guest]: huge unmet expectations. If you have a farm crisis, you know, I don't know what, how that

01:44:45.800 --> 01:44:52.040
[Guest]: will have implications for food security and inflation. Yeah, so I said it's a farm crisis

01:44:52.040 --> 01:44:59.840
[Guest]: and I said it's the growth momentum. And therefore the job crisis, you know, without growth,

01:44:59.840 --> 01:45:05.080
[Guest]: all the youngsters who we've been talking about is the demographic dividend and who,

01:45:05.080 --> 01:45:08.680
[Guest]: you know, we're going to get these jobs and earn, make these incomes and therefore be

01:45:08.680 --> 01:45:14.600
[Guest]: that big market. You know, the whole promise of why there should be investments in India,

01:45:14.600 --> 01:45:19.280
[Guest]: that cycle gets broken and that's the economic point side of it. But, you know, all these

01:45:19.280 --> 01:45:25.600
[Guest]: youngsters with incomes not commensurate with their aspirations and lifestyles not commensurate

01:45:25.600 --> 01:45:31.280
[Guest]: with what they were promised and that demographic dividend will turn into a demographic nightmare

01:45:31.280 --> 01:45:39.880
[Guest]: and it will lead to all kinds of other social and maybe political problems. So that, and

01:45:39.880 --> 01:45:44.880
[Guest]: so I mean, everything that policy determines you, we are already in, on the exports front,

01:45:44.880 --> 01:45:51.200
[Guest]: we are already losing our comparative advantage to other economies that are, you know, sort

01:45:51.200 --> 01:45:57.360
[Guest]: of working very hard and therefore, you know, gaining. And because we are not even, you

01:45:57.360 --> 01:46:03.160
[Guest]: know, working hard to stay where we are, we are losing global position, you know, in textiles,

01:46:03.160 --> 01:46:07.920
[Guest]: et cetera. We were second only to China. We, you know, other countries are now ahead of

01:46:07.920 --> 01:46:13.760
[Guest]: us. We are no longer the second largest exporters. You know, we've slipped on the pecking order

01:46:13.760 --> 01:46:19.680
[Guest]: and you know, these are all cycles. Once you begin to lose your advantage, then it just

01:46:19.680 --> 01:46:27.280
[Guest]: multiplies because these are very highly competitive industries where, you know, small margins

01:46:27.280 --> 01:46:35.560
[Guest]: lead to huge, it's the volumes game. So, you know, you lose an order, you lose big volumes,

01:46:35.560 --> 01:46:40.120
[Guest]: you suddenly slip down the position, you lose further orders to the export side, especially

01:46:40.120 --> 01:46:45.720
[Guest]: where there are labor intensive industries that you begin to hurt. And finally, that

01:46:45.720 --> 01:46:52.200
